an israeli court on sunday sentenced mordechai vanunu, the former nuclear technician who spilled his country's atomic secrets to a british newspaper, to 18 years in prison for treason and espionage
a three-judge panel announced its sentence in a closed-door session at jerusalem's district courthouse shortly after hearing sentencing arguments from both sides
vanunu's trial has been shrouded in secrecy since it began in september. officials said an open trial would harm state security
the crimes for which vanunu was convicted carry a maximum death penalty in israel. however, prosecutors said earlier they would ask for a life sentence, which in israel is limited to 20 years. the court lightened that sentence by two years but its reasons were not made public
according to israeli law, vanunu could be released on good behavior after 12 years. legal commentators said early release was unlikely, given the nature of vanunu's crimes
defense attorney avigdor feldman said he plans to appeal to israel's supreme court
vanunu, 34, was convicted last week of treason and espionage for telling the sunday times of london israel had nuclear weapons
a jewish-born convert to christianity, vanunu worked for 10 years at israel's nuclear facility in the southern desert town of dimona. he then left israel, smuggling out photographs he took from inside the facility
in october 1986, vanunu handed over the photographs and details about israel's nuclear program to the sunday times. based on his information, the newspaper reported israel stockpiled the world's sixth largest nuclear arsenal
israel never responded directly to allegations of its nuclear capacity, saying only it would not be the first country to introduce such weapons into the middle east
several days after the newspaper published his revelations, vanunu disppeared from london
how he returned to israel was never revealed but his family said he was lured to rome by an american woman named cindy, then kidnapped by israeli agents and spirited home to stand trial
during a pre-trial appearance last year, vanunu managed to flash waiting reporters a message scribbled on his hand. in the message, he said he had been kidnapped in rome
after the incident, security precautions around vanunu increased. he was transported to the courthouse in a white van with painted-over windows, and police sirens blared as he was hustled indoors to prevent contact with reporters
vanunu's brother, asher, said following the sentence that his brother had been done an injustice
the trial was not conducted as it should have been,'' asher was quoted as saying by israel army radio. he said an international campaign for vanunu's release would put pressure on the israeli government to release vanunu
during sentencing arguments sunday, judges refused to allow an american expert on international law testify for the defense
the expert, richard falk of princeton university in princeton, n.j., said he was shocked the court refused to let him testify and criticized vanunu's convictions on treason and espionage charges
individual conscience is more important in the nuclear age than the security of the state,'' falk told reporters. ``the state can be wrong.''
vanunu has testified he made his revelations to alert the middle east and the world to the dangers of nuclear weapons, not for personal gain or out of a desire to harm his country
regulars at jd's circle in weren't about to stand by idly when armed robbers burst into the bar and demanded money from owner donna hannum
three or four robbers, one armed with a sawed-off shotgun, entered the bar saturday and ordered about 20 customers to stand back, mrs. hannum said
but some customers got riled when one of the robbers seized the 46-year-old woman, shoved her toward the cash register and grabbed some cash
the guys got mad and they started throwing tables and chairs at the robbers, beer bottle and ashtrays and anything else they could get their hands on,'' mrs. hannum said
a couple of customers wrestled with one of the men
the robbers fired one shotgun blast and a pistol shot into the ceiling to quiet the crowd, she said, before fleeing with an undetermined amount of cash
