john paul noted that it was the third international youth day and called on youth people to discover a more ``profound vocation'' in the church
about 20,000 youths carrying palm or olive branches marched into st. peter's square just as the pope, also carrying a palm branch, led a procession out of st. peter's basilica
the uncertainties of youth are normal. but they can be defeated. ... what is important is to believe that he (god) wants to make each and every one of us free and responsible participants in his plan to save the world,'' the pope told them after the mass
a three-page manuscript by ludwig van beethoven containing a large part of the ``ode to joy'' from his ninth symphony will be sold to the highest bidder, a researcher at sotheby's auction house said sunday
beethoven's untidy brown ink and pencil writing appears to be a draft of alterations to the first, second and last movements and were made after the first performance, said stephen roe, the manuscript expert at sotheby's
nothing was publicly known of its existence until now and it is an astonishing find,'' stephen roe, the manuscript expert at sotheby's, said sunday
roe said the manuscript is privately owned by a collector in another country. he asked not to be identified
it's very much a collector's piece as the `ode to joy' is the composer's most famous passage,'' said roe, who researched the document at beethoven's birthplace in bonn, west germany, now a museum
they didn't know about it there,'' he said
roe said he thought the manuscript would be bought by a collector at the london auction may 6 and could fetch up to $180,000
autograph manuscripts relating to beethoven's symphonies are very rare. complete manuscripts of his 1st, 2nd and 3rd symphonies are lost. his autograph manuscript of the ninth symphony, which he completed in 1824, is in the german state library in east berlin
the changes were incorporated in the first printing of 1826 by schott and sons, the german music publishers
there is another beethoven brown-ink manuscript in the may 6 sale, a sketch-leaf of his early ideas for the slow movement of the ``hammerklavier'' piano sonata, the longest he wrote
the item is estimated at $36,000 to $55,000, roe said
it could be one of those which beethoven amplified and extended from one of the notebooks he carried around on his walks in the countryside around vienna, jotting down ideas in pencil,'' roe said
tamil youths looted and torched at least 25 moslem-owned shops and businesses in the eastern town of kalmunai, police and residents reported sunday
a police officer at the kalmunai police station, speaking on condition of anonymity, said members of the liberation tigers of tamil eelam, the largest tamil militia, were responsible for the attack saturday about 125 miles northeast of colombo
but a roman catholic priest in nearby batticaloa said the looting was done by unemployed tamil youth who were released late last year from jails after being detained as political suspects
there are scores of these tamil youths in the east. they are jobless and penniless,'' said the priest, who also spoke on condition he not be identified. ``they grab every opportunity to make a fast buck. this is a growing problem in the entire area.''
the police official, however, claimed the attack on moslem establishments was a part of ``a grand design of tiger rebels to drive sinhalese and moslem civilians out of the eastern province.''
he said that more than 1,500 moslems fled kalmunai after the attack and sought refuge in mosques and schools in nearby areas
tamil militants have been blamed for killing more than 125 people, most of them sinhalese civilians, in the eastern province since march 2 when the latest round of violence erupted
officials say tamil militants are engaged in driving away sinhalese and moslem residents of the eastern province to ensure complete dominance in the region
most of the tamils are hindus. sinhalese are mostly buddhists although some of them are moslem
tamil rebels claim the government is deliberately resettling members of the majority sinhalese community in the east to upset traditional tamil control of the area
tamils, who make up 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people, say they are discriminated against by the sinhalese, who control the government and the military. tamil rebels are fighting for a separate homeland in the northern and eastern provinces, where most of them live
india and sri lanka signed a peace accord last july to end the tamil ethnic crisis but tamil tigers have not honored the pact. more than 50,000 indian peacekeeping troops are in sri lanka to disarm the rebels and enforce the peace accord that grants some autonomy to the tamils
yasser arafat's fatah guerrillas have taken control of lebanon's largest palestinian refugee camp after a two-day wave of violence left five people dead, police said sunday
the latest victims were a fatah guerrilla and a palestinian woman killed saturday in a shootout at the ein el-hilweh camp on the outskirts of this southern port city, police reported
they said guerrillas of abu nidal's radical fatah-revolutionary council opened fire on the fatah fighter, identified as haitham diab, when he failed to stop at an one of their checkpoints in the sprawling shantytown
diab's killing touched off a brief firefight between arafat's supporters and abu nidal's guerrillas in which the woman passer-by, badea oweida, was killed, police said
there have been frequent clashes between supporters of arafat's palestine liberation organization, including fatah, and rival syrian-backed factions as well as abu nidal's group
police said the latest wave of violence that flared friday prompted the plo's pro-arafat military police, known as the ``armed struggle corps,'' to take charge of ein el-hilweh's security
on friday, gunmen ambushed the motorcade of farid hourani, fatah's military commander in the camp, killing him and two of his bodyguards. nine other hourani aides were wounded
police said there was no link between friday's ambush and saturday's shootout
but the two incidents have led to an agreement to turn over the camp's security to the `armed struggle corps,''' a police spokesman said
units of the force patrolled the camp's narrow alleyways on foot and in jeeps sunday without challenge from arafat's rivals, police said
the agreement was reached during a meeting late saturday between arafat's representatives, abu nidal's aides and the ``popular committee'' which runs the day-to-day affairs of the camp's 60,000 refugees
less than a month before the filing deadline, fewer than half of americans have finished their tax returns. but refunds are bigger, the irs is doing a better job answering questions, and taxpayers are making fewer mistakes than had been expected
i'm happy to report that so far, the filing season is going much as we had predicted and hoped,'' irs commissioner lawrence b. gibbs tells audiences
the internal revenue service is almost 3 percent behind last year's pace in processing returns, but blames that chiefly on taxpayers' slowness in filing this year. officials say there is nothing to signal a repeat of 1985 when faulty computer programs set off a chain of events that resulted in the worst filing season in modern times
through march 18, 47.6 million returns had been logged at the 10 irs service centers. just under 35 million had been processed
more than seven of every 10 returns are qualifying for refunds: 25 million refunds totaling $20 billion, an average of $809 apiece. the number of refunds is down slightly and the average is up a bit from 1987
so far this year, about 44 percent of the 107 million expected individual returns have been filed. at the same stage last year, the irs had received almost 46 percent of the 104 million that eventually were filed
the irs has come under heavy criticism for having given the correct answer to only 74.8 percent of taxpayers' calls for assistance earlier this year. but in recent weeks, gibbs says, the accuracy rate has crept up to nearly 78 percent as telephone ``assistors'' become more familiar with the new law
perhaps the most surprising statistic is that taxpayers are making only 2 percent more mistakes than they were at this time last year. according to the most recent estimate, that's nearly 5.5 million errors _ a number that had been expected to be far higher since this is the first year that returns reflect the massive 1986 tax revision
the low error rate comes despite reports that many taxpayers are finding some of the changes much more confusing than congress anticipated
one possible explanation is that most of the confusion comes from tax changes that affect more-affluent taxpayers, such as complicated new forms for calculating passive losses and taxes on children's income
these taxpayers are less likely to qualify for refunds and, thus, are in no hurry to file. their mistakes likely would come later in the filing season
the new law cut tax rates, increased the personal exemption to $1,900, boosted the standard deductions for non-itemizers, and reduced or eliminated several deductions
but most of the mistakes are not resulting from those changes. taxpayers instead are having problems with their arithmetic, misreading the tax tables and misunderstanding a new provision that prevents one person from being claimed as a dependent on two tax returns
one of the most common mistakes on the single-page form 1040ez, which may be used only by single taxpayers whose taxable income is under $50,000, is on the bottom line. many users of this form _ as well as some who file the longer form 1040a _ are unable to subtract actual tax liability from the amount withheld and get the correct answer
a common error among itemizers is incorrect addition or subtraction on schedule a, where deductions are listed. on 1040a and 1040, some are unable to multiply the number of personal exemptions by $1,900 and get the correct answer
some mistakes are clearly a result of carelessness. many filers of 1040a are neglecting to write how much tax was withheld. other taxpayers use the wrong income figure for determining how much tax they owe
but the most common mistake is a misunderstanding of the standard deduction and personal exemption allowed a taxpayer who can be claimed as a dependent by someone else. this affects a student with some income whose main support is provided by a parent, or a parent supported by a son or daughter
a single person who cannot be claimed by another gets the full $2,540 standard deduction and the full $1,900 personal exemption. but a student, for example, who can be claimed by a parent gets no exemption and may be entitled to a standard deduction of as little as $500, depending on income
some taxpayers are neglecting to answer whether they may be claimed by another. others are taking the wrong standard deduction
if the irs can correct your errors _ such as arithmetic or failing to take the correct standard deduction _ it will
but the irs will put your return aside and write you for more information if, for example, your schedule a deductions don't add up; you neglect to say whether you may be claimed as a dependent by another; you don't sign your return or your neglect to attach your w-2
the recent elections have further polarized politics in el salvador and handed a major defeat to the political center, cultivated by the united states as an antidote to extremism
the rightist victory in legislative and municipal elections march 20 sets the stage for the escalation of leftist guerrilla conflict in this country already ravaged by eight years of civil war
the nature of pre-election violence, which included car bombs and club-wielding masked youths rampaging through the capital, augured badly for those who had hoped that six years of civilian rule by the christian democrats would promote moderation in the search for solutions to el salvador's problems
no country in the hemisphere gets more u.s. assistance than el salvador, which president reagan has held up as an example of success in washington's avowed policy of fostering democracy in latin america
this massachusetts-sized country of 5 million people received about $550 million in u.s. military and economic aid last year. u.s. assistance has totaled $3.5 billion since 1981
a rightist party, linked in the early 1980s to death squads responsible for thousands of political murders, won a landslide victory in the municipal and legislative elections
liberty is written with blood. ... el salvador is the tomb where the reds will meet their end,'' goes the party anthem of the republican nationalist alliance, or arena
the party captured a majority in the 60-seat national assembly and most of the country's municipalities
sigifredo ochoa perez, a retired army colonel and one of the party's ideologues, wednesday called for a crackdown on leftists active outside guerrilla ranks
in the 10 days before the vote, left-wing university groups and labor organizations staged several anti-government marches in the capital. the marchers, their faces covered with bandannas and carrying two-by-fours studded with nails, commandeered buses to block side streets, burned telephone exchange boxes and set fire to several vehicles
police exercised restraint, resorting only once to tear gas to disperse the demonstrators
we cannot allow this to continue, the destruction of state property, private property,'' ochoa said on a morning tv news program. ``we have to impose law and order.''
for their part, marxist guerrillas waging the stalemated war against the centrist christian democratic government plan to broaden their campaign, according to rebel documents captured by government forces
the documents outline a plan the guerrillas call ``fire.'' it calls for formation and indoctrination of ``mass organizations'' _ mostly among students and labor union people _ ``to deepen the crisis.''
its authors, reportedly members of the guerrilla general command, said the government's options _ to increase repression or continue allowing the demonstrators to act with relative impunity _ both favored the revolution
if they crack down on a big scale the insurrection will increase in response to the repression, and if they do not, insurrection will advance as a result of the crisis and hunger,'' it says
it says if ``fire'' succeeds in forging a mass front, 1988 provides circumstances propitious for ``the seizure of power.''
guerrilla commander joaquin villalobos predicted last tuesday that as a result of the election, ``the country will become ungovernable.''
speaking on radio vencermos, the rebels' clandestine station, he said the rightist victory favored the rebels by giving the people ``a clear choice.''
alfredo cristiani, president of arena, told the associated press his party would try to hammer out with other parties in the assembly a peace proposal to submit to the guerrillas
if the guerrillas do not accept the proposal, which will be the result of a national consensus, they do not leave any other way out but a military solution,'' he said. he indicated that would mean stepped-up combat
ruben zamora, vice-president of the democratic revolutionary front, told the ap wednesday he did not believe the vote indicated the electorate's shift to the right. the revolutionary front is allied with the guerrillas and declined to take part in the elections
what happened was that the electorate punished the christian democrats for all the promises they did not fulfill,'' he said
president jose napoleon duarte was elected in 1984 on a platform of ending the war and improving the average family's lot. the war continues, unemployment is about 40 percent and inflation is running at about 40 percent annually
the victory improves arena's prospects in presidential elections set for next march
adolfo rey prendes, the front-runner for the christian democratic presidential nomination, told reporters: ``if arena takes power, other parties' possibilities will be diminished. the democratic process will be restricted.''
douglas grant mine, formerly news editor in argentina, now covers central america for the associated press
in roman catholic areas of west belfast, british soldiers with rifles cocked patrol grimy streets whose graffiti-filled walls boast of irish republican army killings
a five-minute drive away, the center of the city bustles with shoppers. after nightfall dozens of bars, restaurants and nightclubs come alive with northern irelanders determined, despite 19 years of conflict, to enjoy themselves
like beirut, belfast is a city compartmentalized by sectarian strife and shadowy armed factions calling themselves ``paramilitaries.'' the front lines are the street junctions where working-class catholic and protestant neighborhoods adjoin
murderous rampages this month at two ira funerals, in which five people died, inflamed the nerves of a city that has lived with violence for nearly 20 years of the so-called ``troubles.''
on both sides of the sectarian divide, there is frustration, anger, and a longing for peace. for some years, with the violence in a sharp decline and signs emerging of economic rejuvenation, optimists dared to hope belfast was getting a fresh chance. but with the latest violence, and no sign of a political solution, many people now talk of leaving
the outlawed ira and its legal political wing, sinn fein, remain committed to ending british rule and uniting the protestant-majority province with the overwhelmingly catholic republic of ireland 
the protestants, under the banner ``no surrender,'' are equally determined to keep northern ireland in the united kingdom
a cartoon in dublin's irish times noted that while cease-fires were being discussed in nicaragua and afghanistan, ``in northern ireland, after almost 20 years of fighting, we are discussing the policing of future funerals.''
the sense of conflict never-ending is shared by young people who have known nothing else
i'm really fed up with the trouble _ on both sides,'' said gail mccann, 23, a student at queen's university in belfast
when i get my degree, i think i'll go away and work if things keep going like this. there's no future here.''
ms. mccann was part of a huge and mainly protestant crowd which thronged the grounds of city hall on thursday for a memorial service for two british corporals who were beaten up and stripped almost naked by mourners at an ira funeral on march 19 and then shot dead by ira gunmen
the murders climaxed two weeks of rising tension after british commandos shot dead three ira guerrillas who were unarmed but allegedly plotting a bombing in gibraltar
on march 16, a protestant gunman attacked mourners at the guerrillas' funeral in the catholic milltown cemetery, killing three people and wounding 68. the soldiers were murdered at the funeral for one of the milltown victims, an ira man
i don't want to be called irish anymore,'' a government architect who identified himself only as ivan said at the memorial service where some people brought british flags and wreaths bearing the initials of queen elizabeth ii
it's savage _ bestial. i can't see any future,'' ivan said. ``i think until children are educated together, it won't change.'' most northern ireland schools are segregated according to religion
bring back capital punishment for both sides,'' shouted a middle-aged man. ``but start with sinn fein,'' chimed in a young man
three miles away in the heart of catholic west belfast, an elderly man stood at the door of the andersonstown social club, an irish nationalist haunt overlooking the garbage-strewn parking lot where the soldiers' bodies were dumped
it's just another day to us. there's still plenty of tension,'' he said
on andersonstown road, where the soldiers were seized, two unemployed catholics objected to the fuss about the murders
to them the real outrages were in gibraltar when commandos reputedly from the elite special air service unit opened fire on unarmed ira members, and in milltown when the protestant let loose with pistol and grenades
the sas men who killed the three will get a medal, so why don't they give a medal to the men who killed them two soldiers?'' asked one, who gave only his first name, liam
it's been the same for the last 20 years _ depression and frustration,'' said francis mccann, 29. ``there's nothing they (catholics) can do about it, but they won't take abuse anymore.''
on the catholic falls road, the latest graffiti makes sas stand for ``stripped and shot.'' on the adjoining protestant shankill road, a fresh slogan says, ``three dead with one stone.'' the milltown gunman's name is michael stone
in prosperous north belfast, where middle-class protestants and catholics live peacefully side by side, 26-year-old karen mccomish said, ``you can forget about it here to a certain extent.''
but after the events of last week, it's hard to deal with, but it's either that or get out,'' she added
big-name london stores have moved in to central belfast, nearly 200 new restaurants and several dozen nightclubs have opened in the last three years and tourism is up 14 percent
but the fear endures. ``it's so bad, i want to go away,'' says mary eakin, a public relations executive. ``but my husband says, `mary, i love ireland.'''
police charged a third man sunday in connection with the slayings of two british army officers who were beaten by mourners at an irish republican army funeral and shot
shop manager thomas hawkins, 35, of belfast, appeared in belfast magistrates court where he was charged with withholding information about the murders and allowing his premises to be used by terrorists
he did not enter a plea and was ordered held in custody until his next court appearance in 14 days
cpls. david howes, 23, and derek wood, 24, were killed march 19 after they drove up to the funeral procession of ira member kevin brady. mourners dragged them from their car and beat them unconscious. they were later shot behind a wall in a soccer stadium
two other men, alexander murphy, 30, and henry maguire, 28, were charged friday with the soldiers' slayings and ordered saturday to remain in custody until their next court appearance on april 22
the royal ulster constabulary, northern ireland's police force, said it was still holding two other men for questioning
details of the charges against hawkins were not revealed
the detective in charge of the investigation told the court saturday that police have evidence, including bloodstains, clothing fibres and footprints, linking murphy and maguire with the march 19 killings
comedian bob hope joined a host of celebrities to raise funds to combat aids in his first public appearance since having prostate surgery a week ago
i think that we can use all our talent, all our money in the world to help win this war,'' said hope, who performed a five-minute comedy routine at the event, ``hollywood's salute to broadway,'' saturday
hope joined actress susan anton, comic jay leno, broadway choreographer tommy tune and others to raise funds for 14 programs and organizations dealing with acquired immune deficiency syndrome
surgeon general c. everett koop, who received an award in recognition of his efforts to promote awareness of the disease, said the nearly 700 children born with aids represent the biggest tragedy of the epidemic
of all the things in this whole miserable mess, this is the thing that is most depressing to me ... profoundly depressing to me,'' he said
reviewers concurred. despite the years, rudolf nureyev's still the greatest
nureyev, who turned 50 on march 17, performed for the last time the role of siegfried in tchaikovsky's ``swan lake'' at the vienna state opera on friday and saturday
it was a sentimental end to the vienna dance '88 festival. nureyev first performed the role, which he choreographed, on oct. 15, 1964, at the state opera
the russian-born star and his illustrious partner, dame margot fonteyn, got a record 89 curtain calls for that premiere
the official newspaper wiener zeitung called this weekend's performances a ``farewell to a legend.''
there is no reason to mourn the golden era of the ballet star. for what nurev has (of course) forfeited in terms of power, elegance and precision, he compensates for with stage presence, personality and radiance,'' the government daily said
donald j. trump told a newspaper he plans to make new york's famed plaza hotel ``the most luxurious hotel in the world,'' but, uncharacteristically, the eponymous developer will keep his name off the landmark building
it's got the most important name in the world and it's going to remain that way,'' the new york times quoted trump as saying in its sunday editions
trump outbid two other manhattan developers and bought the posh hotel for $390 million from texas multimillionaire robert m. bass and aoki corp. of japan, the times reported
trump, whose other properties include the glitzy trump tower in manhattan and trump plaza in atlantic city, n.j., said he signed a contract for the hotel friday and would take possession in 120 days
the hotel's new president will be trump's wife, ivana, who will be paid ``$1 a year plus all the dresses she can buy,'' trump said
debi thomas, the u.s. figure skating champion and olympic bronze medalist, sunday announced her march 15 marriage to a university of colorado student
i did not want to this news to detract from my focus on the world championships (last week),'' thomas said. ``now that the world championships are over, i want to let all my friends and supporters know how happy i am.''
thomas' husband is brian vanden hogen, 23
the two met at the university of colorado when thomas moved there last year to train with her coach, alex mcgowan, and they were married in boulder
my husband will travel with me to some of the upcoming skating exhibitions. i am thrilled.''
there will be a tour of europe following the world championships and then there will be another tour in the united states until june
thomas, of san jose, calif., celebrated her 21st birthday friday but came in third in the final standings of the women's event saturday. katarina witt of east germany, the olympic gold medalist, won the championships
edward zwick and marshall herskovitz, creators and executive producers of abc's ``thirtysomething,'' said they wanted to deal with mundane concerns like in-law troubles and choosing baby sitters that most other television shows ignore
it was our aim to explore these more delicate concerns of life. i wanted to deal with smaller issues that don't get explored,'' said zwick, who joined herskovitz and several of the show's writers and cast members to discuss the program before about 600 fans thursday at the los angeles county museum of art
the show, which explores the lives of seven aging baby boomers, has been praised by some critics for its realism but criticized by others for its ``yuppie whining.''
to some degree, whining and moaning is a celebration of life,'' zwick said
herskovitz admitted the program's situations don't appeal to everyone
if it doesn't go along with someone's existence, it will turn them off,'' he said
actress audrey hepburn said sunday she thinks of her famine-relief work as a ``mission _ and one i do out of great love.''
the actress, who returned recently from a tour of ethiopia as a special ambassador for unicef, said the scenes of famine she encountered there were ``heart-breaking.''
it will get better if we all help,'' she told reporters at london's heathrow airport upon her arrival from toronto, canada
what the people need more than anything is rain, she said. ``but in the meantime, what they need is continued relief, food and the means to preserve and contain their water
they don't have enough reservoirs or wells. the day they have that will be the day that drought won't mean famine anymore.'' battles</head>
iranian gunboats rocketed an indian tanker in the persian gulf sunday, setting its engine room ablaze and wounding a crewmen, gulf-based shipping executives reported
iran and iraq fired missiles into each other's capitals in a brutal long-range duel. in northeast iraq, iran said its troops punched deeper into enemy territory, occupying strategic heights that overlook a key hydroelectric dam
both countries reported extensive civilian casualties in the missile war
shipping officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the 24,529-ton jainarayan vyas, owned by the shipping corp. of india, was en route to the saudi arabian port of jubail to load petrochemicals when it was hit
they said salvage tugs and the crew struggled for three hours to extinguish a fire in the engine room
the tanker was attacked just before noon about 40 miles from the iranian-held abu musa island. the island serves as a base for revolutionary guards who attack neutral ships in armed speedboats in retaliation for iraqi air raids on iranian tankers
the jainarayan vyas was hit in apparent retaliation for iraqi air raids on iranian tankers overnight friday
a danish supertanker, the 337,700-ton karama maersk, was initially believed to have also been attacked near abu musa
but shipping sources said the vessel had only relayed a distress call from the stricken indian vessel
iran and iraq, at war since september 1980, have attacked about 500 ships of various nationalities in the gulf in the ``tanker war.'' about 300 seamen have been killed
iraq fired a long-range al hussein missile sunday into tehran, a city of 6 million, at 7.30 a.m. after vowing to ``level iran's cities,'' the official iraqi news agency reported
minutes later, another missile was launched on tehran and two into the central city of isfahan, ancient capital of the persian empire, ina said
the iranians said the missiles hit residential neighborhoods, causing unspecified civilian casualties
the islamic republic news agency, also monitored in nicosia, said revolutionary guards fired two missiles at baghdad
the agency said the missiles were aimed at ``two military targets'' in retaliation for iraqi missiles that hit tehran saturday. iran said the missiles killed at least seven civilians and hit an orphanage
baghdad radio reported only one iranian missile hit baghdad, home to 5 million. the missile exploded in a residential district and demolishing houses, shops and cars. it said there were ``many civilians killed or wounded, including women and children.''
iraq has fired 120 long-range missiles into tehran, isfahan and the holy city of qom, seat of iran's religious hierarchy, since feb. 29
the iranians have reported firing 45 long-range missiles into baghdad and dozens of short-range projectiles into other iraqi cities in that period
tehran radio reported that the iranians also fired four missiles at ``industrial and military installations'' in the strategic southern iraqi port of basra, and two other border towns further north sunday
the iranian broadcast reported 1,500 iraqi soldiers were killed and 350 wounded in fighting with revolutionary guards for control of lake darbandikhan, high in the kurdistan mountains
the iranian agency said 20 tanks and armored vehicles were destroyed and 15 captured when iranian troops beat back an abortive iraqi counter-attack
it said revolutionary guards captured the shaakh shamshir heights overlooking a big hydroelectric dam on the southernmost point of the 10-mile long lake darbandikhan
the facility provides most of the power for the region as well as the capital baghdad, 120 miles to the southeast
tehran's communiques said revolutionary guards had battled to within three miles of the dam. irna said the revolutionary guards used speedboats to outflank iraqi forces on the southern shore of the lake while artillery and fighter-bombers pounded iraqi positions
iraq acknowledged saturday it has lost ground to the iranians, who say they have pushed 10 miles into kurdistan
if iranian claims are true, they are now 70 miles from iraq's kirkuk oilfield, which accounts for 1.5 million barrels of oil a day, more than half iraq's oil production, vital for its war effort
in baghdad, the official newspaper al-jumhouriya said in an editorial: ``iraq is determined to utilize all capabilities and means to decimate the invaders and purge the land inch by inch.''
al-thawra, another government newspaper, said: ``we defend ourselves with all available means.''
the editorials and a declaration saturday by the ruling revolutionary command council hinted that iraq had used chemicals weapons that iran claims killed about 5,000 iraqi kurds
the rebellious kurds have long fought the baghdad government for autonomy
security forces shot and killed four people believed to be kurdish guerrillas during a clash sunday in southeastern turkey, the anatolia news agency reported
the agency said the four were hiding in a cave and opened fire on government troops searching the area near bahce hamlet in adiyaman province
security forces found one g-3 automatic rifle, one soviet-made kalashnikov rifle, two pistols, three hand grenades and ammunition in the cave, the agency said
most guerrillas in the region are affiliated with the kurdish labor party, which seeks to establish a marxist state in parts of southeastern and eastern turkey
about 700 civilians and military personnel and an equal number of kurdish rebels have been killed since the group began attacking military targets and villages in august 1984
ethnic kurds make up one-fifth of turkey's population of 52 million
an unexploded bomb was found early sunday outside the brussels office of the african national congress, the banned south african opposition movement, police reported
the neighborhood was isolated while bomb disposal experts neutralized and removed the explosive device, which police only described as ``strong.''
a few weeks ago, two shots were fired at the same office while anc representatives were inside. nobody was injured and no one was arrested
the anc is the main guerrilla group fighting south africa's white-led government
april fools day was the date of the first two save the pun dinners, but good friday falls on april 1 this year, causing ``mass'' confusion among punsters
instead, the dinner is sharing april 4 with the `oh! punning day' of the chicago white sox,'' joked joyce heitler, the dinner's organizer. ``we'll both have a ball.''
heitler is head of the chicago chapter of the international save the pun foundation
why save the pun? because it's in danger of extinction,'' she said
but heitler made it clear during an interview saturday that the pun still is very much alive, at least in her conversation
we'll have everything on the menu from soup to nuts, but we promise not to serve soup to nuts,'' heitler said
we would have had alphabet soup but we didn't want guests groping for words,'' she added
more than 200 punsters are expected to attend the dinner at which the foundation will celebrate its 10th anniversary and present its first punster of the year award
we asked members to send us their votes, and there were a great many votes for president reagan. they feel america is safer with a `ray gun' in the white house,'' said john crosbie, founder and chairman of the ``bored'' at the foundation, which he says has 78,000 members worldwide
reagan didn't win, but the identity of the award's recipient is being kept a secret until the dinner
crosbie, a toronto writer and marketing consultant, said in a telephone interview saturday from his canadian home that there also is a serious side to puns
statistics tell us that one in five people in the united states and canada is functionally illiterate, and if we can get kids to see the fun there is with words, we can get them interested in reading,'' he said
teachers and professors are using our newsletters in the classroom and getting students to enjoy reading,'' said crosbie, who publishes a newsletter for punsters that costs $19 a year
heitler, who teaches kindergarten at a roman catholic school on the city's north side, said her pupils like puns and she uses them in the classroom
heitler, who also works as a clown, magician and publicist, thinks english is the best language for punsters because almost every word has a double meaning and punsters delight in twisting the language
while she acknowledges many people cannot stomach puns or punsters, heitler notes that punning has been around for centuries and says the ranks of famous punsters include groucho marx, shakespeare and queen elizabeth i
shakespeare had 1,062 puns in his plays,'' noted crosbie
more than 7,000 residents were evacuated and 14,000 ordered to stay indoors sunday while dutch army explosives experts defused a huge bomb from world war ii
no one was injured in the operation in a densely populated residential district. life returned to normal after authorities removed the bomb's ignition shortly after 4 p.m
sunday's $3.15 million operation involved more than 2,000 police and city officials. it was the largest evacuation since 1953, when massive floods in the southwestern netherlands killed more than 1,700 people
at least 14 people were arrested for ignoring the order to stay indoors
authorities also vacated an indoor skating rink to accomodate up to 700 pets whose owners insisted on their evacuation. but only four cats, a dog and a handful of birds were taken there, said city hall spokesman ben van der schaaf
the 1,000-pound bomb was dropped by a typhoon bomber of the british royal air force on nov. 29, 1944, during what was meant to be a precision raid on the local headquarters of the nazi security service, or sicherheitsdienst
the building, 500 yards from the site of sunday's operation in a densely populated inner-city district, was only slightly damaged in the raid, and most of the 61 killed were local residents
the raf bomb tore into a back yard only a few yards from an apartment block. it was soon forgotten and lay buried more than 30 feet deep until a resident reminded city hall of its presence during renovation work last may
all residents living within 300 yards of the bomb were evacuated. police searched their homes to make sure they were empty, shut off gas and water mains and sealed front doors
all residents living 300 to 600 yards away were ordered to close their doors and windows, draw their curtains and stay indoors
two army explosives experts using a 50-yard rope then unscrewed the ignition of the 5{-foot-long bomb, said their chief, maj. adriaan sprangemeijer
the tensest moment of the defusing operation came as the pair had to leave their heavily armored cabin to pull out the ignition with a pair of forceps, sprangemeijer said
it's scary,'' said 16-year old daniella barto as she leafed through a magazine at the energy hall sports center, where about 350 evacuees were spending the day
daniella's father, jozef barto, said he remembered the 1944 bombing raid by four typhoon squadrons of the raf's 14th wing
it was terrible (but) at least i came through o.k.,'' said barto, a 69-year-old retired bicycle repairman
although the authorities had launched a massive media effort weeks in advance of the operation, police said they had to break open more than 100 homes of people who were not there and had not handed in their keys in advance. burglars</head>
as they fight a 23-count indictment, the key figures in the iran-contra affair may take a cue from two watergate burglars and assert a ``good faith'' belief that the white house gave them a lawful covert mission to perform
bernard l. barker and eugenio r. martinez paved the way for this defense by winning reversal of their convictions for a burglary they conducted on assignment from the nixon white house
the 1976 appellate court ruling said the trial court erred by preventing the two watergate foot soldiers from putting forth the ``good faith'' defense at their trial
daniel e. schultz, the lawyer who represented barker and martinez, said in an interview that iran-contra defendants richard v. secord and albert hakim would have the best chance of asserting the defense
secord and hakim were private businessmen recruited by a white house aide, oliver l. north, to secretly arm the nicaraguan contra rebels when such assistance was banned by congress and to arrange for covert arms shipments to iran, which were authorized by president reagan
schultz said north also might be able to use the ``good faith'' defense because he has asserted that he received lawful directions from his superiors _ his boss at the national security council, john m. poindexter, and the late cia director, william j. casey
i never carried out a single act, not one ... in which i did not have authority from my superiors,'' north told the congressional iran-contra committees last july 7
the fourth defendant, poindexter, would have a difficult time using the defense, schultz said. as north's boss at the nsc, poindexter was at a level where he was making decisions rather than taking orders
in fact, poindexter told congress july 16 that he ``personally approved'' the diversion of profits from the iran arms sales to the contras and kept the decision from the president
secord and hakim have excellent arguments on a good faith belief'' of participating in a lawful activity, said joseph digenova, the former chief federal prosecutor for the district of columbia and now a private attorney
their orders were from high government officials. it's clear in cases like this that hakim and secord will be able to argue they had authority to do this
the independent counsel will want to show their perception of authority was skewed by their desire to make money.''
the indictment accused the defendants of embezzling more than $17 million from the arms sales to iran _ the difference between the $30 million paid by the iranians and the $12.2 million turned over to the u.s. government
the grand jury said the defendants conspired to ``secretly and deceptively'' divert millions of dollars from those profits. the indictment said that secord, hakim and north personally profited from the diversion and that the nicaraguan contras received assistance in violation of a congressional ban on such aid
barker and martinez were convicted in the september 1971 burglary at the office of daniel ellsberg's psychiatrist, dr. louis j. fielding. ellsberg was a former defense department official who leaked the secret pentagon papers that were critical of the vietnam war
the two burglars were part of a secret white house unit _ known as the plumbers _ that was established to investigate leaks of classified information. they also were among the men who broke into the democratic party offices in the watergate building in washington
barker was a former cia operative, and martinez was on a cia retainer when they were recruited for the fielding burglary by a white house official, e. howard hunt
after their conviction, they appealed successfully to the u.s. court of appeals for the district of columbia. they argued the trial judge erred when he refused to admit the defendants' claim of a good faith reliance on hunt's authority to assign them to a lawful operation. after the reversal, the government declined to retry the defendants, who had pleaded guilty and served time for the watergate break-in
in the 2-1 appellate opinion, judge malcolm richard wilkey wrote, ``there was abundant evidence in the case from which the jury could have found that the defendants honestly and reasonably believed they were engaged in a top-secret national security operation lawfully authorized by a government intelligence agency.''
schultz said that successful use of the good faith defense must depend on the background and knowledge of the defendant asserting it
in the barker-martinez case, the appellate court recognized that the assignment from hunt was entirely consistent with the defendants' prior covert missions
both testified at trial that they had no reason to question hunt's credentials,'' the appeals court said. ``he clearly worked for the white house and had a well-known background with the cia. during the entire time they worked for the cia, neither barker nor martinez was ever shown any credentials by their superiors. not once did they receive written instructions. ..
nevertheless, they testified, their understanding was always that those operations had been authorized by the government of the united states
hunt's instructions and actions were in complete accord with what their previous experience had taught them to expect.''
in the iran-contra case, secord _ a retired air force major general _ had expertise in covert missions. that prior experience, including the way he received assignments, could determine if ``there was a red flag for him'' in the iran-contra affair, schultz said
schultz said poindexter would have a problem with the good faith defense because the higher someone rises in job responsibility, ``the more suspect your claim of lack of knowledge'' about legality
north is somewhere in the upper middle,'' schultz said. ``he's not the legal adviser, he's an operational man. he can present a very credible picture of someone who had every reason to believe'' the iran-contra decisions were lawful
if hakim was not accustomed to covert operations, in which the authority of the supervisor is rarely questioned, he may actually have a weaker case, schultz said. without having received such assignments, he could be expected to raise questions about lawfulness, schultz said
abraham lincoln paid just $1,500 for the only house he ever owned, but nearly 150 years later $2.2 million has been spent to fix it up before it's reopened to the public this summer
back at that time, he got a good buy for his money,'' said gentry davis of the national park service. ``it was a corner lot and a prime location with easy access to downtown.''
a three-year renovation of lincoln's two-story frame house will enter its final phase wednesday when workers remove a vinyl polyester shroud that cloaked the structure and allowed restoration to continue through the winter
workers then will put the finishing touches on the exterior and begin grading and landscaping
at this point, we're on budget, on time and on schedule,'' said richard a. lusardi, the park service's maintenance chief for the project. ``it will be ready for the grand reopening june 16.''
once it reopens park service officials expect a tourist boom, with the number of visitors swelling from the 500,000 average of past years to as many as 1 million annually
lincoln was 35, a prosperous lawyer and a former state legislator considering a bid for congress when he moved his family into the house in 1844, five years after it was built
he and his wife, mary todd lincoln, and their four sons lived in the house until 1861 when he moved to the white house
the house, administered by the park service since 1972, has undergone several renovations, most recently in the 1950s, but the current effort stresses historical accuracy
features added after lincoln left for washington have been removed. the park service has installed fire detection and suppression systems, burglary monitors and humidity controls, but they are neatly disguised
the exterior has been painted in an authentic color for the time _ mocha brown. insulation and a vapor barrier were installed in the walls, which were replastered
the interior is being refurnished with exact reproductions of wallpaper and rugs
the furniture had suffered ultraviolet light damage, and the house had no air conditioning prior to the restoration, causing glue joints to dry out and separate,'' said larry blake, the park service's site chief for visitor services
some additional period pieces are being added to fill out the house. they are mostly knick-knacks and accessories on bureaus, for example, to add a lived-in look.''
to ensure the restoration is as accurate as possible, restorers analyzed paint and reviewed records of shops where the family bought household goods
it's almost like trying to solve a mystery,'' blake said. ``you have to do a lot of detective work.''
the finish on the woodwork, for example, was a very dark varnish. but a paint analysis showed it should be off-white, and the change has been made
every day a new question comes up that doesn't have an easy answer,'' said davis, superintendent of the lincoln home for the park service
one of the biggest surprises for restorers was the discovery of a cache of documents inside a kitchen wall. the items, which will be displayed at the house, date to the 16th president's days as a congressman and include part of an envelope addressed and signed by lincoln, four letters to him and a printed anti-slavery speech
the cost of the renovation is being borne by taxpayers, not by tourists. a stipulation in the will of robert lincoln, the president's oldest son, who deeded the property to the state of illinois, prohibits visitors from being charged
the reagan administration has spent more than $70 million since 1981 trying to persuade america's teen-agers to abstain from premarital sex _ a small sum in an era of trillion-dollar budgets
but there's a problem, says american civil liberties union attorney janet benshoof. she charges the money from the adolescent family life act is going to religious organizations to promote their beliefs, a clear violation of the constitutional separation of church and state
our position is this is a statute which funds religious organizations to teach sex education,'' said benshoof, head of the aclu's reproductive freedom project
since you can't fund these organizations to teach math, this is unconstitutional. ... they're blatantly funding religious groups to teach not only religion, but anti-abortion propaganda.''
the federal department of health and human services disagrees, and the case goes before the u.s. supreme court on wednesday. the arguments indirectly pit the aclu against president reagan, an outspoken proponent of what he once called ``my adolescent family life program.''
a decision in the case is expected some time before the court's july 3 summer break. it should provide a first look at newly appointed justice anthony m. kennedy's views on family life questions
currently 82 organizations split $10 million in federal money under the program. each applicant's program is reviewed for religious content before funds are shipped; more than half is spent to assist pregnant teens
at least one organization has lost its funds in the past three years for crossing the bounds out of the secular domain
the adolescent family life program has been under fire since 1983, two years after the bill was sponsored by former alabama sen. jeremiah denton and quickly approved by congress
denton, a staunch reagan republican, believed it provided an alternative to planned parenthood and could reduce teen-age pregnancies, but opponents derisively termed it the ``federal chastity act.'' denton said he feels the act's goals are still valid
there should be a place, if the federal government gets involved as it has with planned parenthood, which permits a church-affiliated group to work with a child,'' he said, adding he was disheartened the case had gone this far
it's ok to say no,'' denton continued. ``i don't think it's a right-wing nut idea. i just hope the idea doesn't go away.''
the program's impact around the country is uncertain. figures from the national institute for adolescent pregnancies indicate the number of annual teen-age pregnancies remained at about 1 million for 1986 and again in 1987
in legal briefs filed in the supreme court action, the government acknowledged some ``serious problems'' in the church-state area of the family life program, but claimed they have been corrected. there was no further on-the-record comment from the government
it is in litigation, and we have a policy about not commenting on cases in litigation,'' said nabers cabaniss, deputy assistant secretary for population affairs in health and human services
through it all the bill has never lost the support of reagan, who called a u.s. district court decision which struck down the program as ``a perversion of the first amendment,'' which mandates separation of church and state
benshoof, in turn, blames reagan for much of her organization's busy schedule over the past eight years
since 1980, reagan has obviously used his power over executive agencies to implement anti-abortion laws, whether or not congress has approved them,'' she said
as evidence, she pointed to a case still in litigation involving health and human services regulations issued jan. 29 which limit access to information about abortion at more than 4,000 federally funded family planning clinics
the changes violate the first amendment and turn health officials into ``mouthpieces for the reagan administration's anti-abortion ideology,'' she charged when filing suit against the regulations. law</head>
this northeastern florida city has a booming economy, a revitalized downtown and an active community leadership. and now a new ordinance may help reduce its stench
if there's one issue that transcends this city, rich and poor, black and white, it's the odor issue,'' said first-term mayor tommy hazouri. ``odor is the only issue keeping us from being a world-class city.''
few of the city's 610,000 residents, who've lived with the industrial odor for four decades, would argue that the air needs cleaning
i'll tell you exactly what the air smells like. it's like being locked in a port-o-let at the county fair. there's no escape,'' said homeowner jeanne oster
you never get used to it,'' said yellow cab driver joe greene. ``i pick people up in my cab at the airport and coming down (interstate) 95 the smell hits them, and it gets real quiet and i think to myself, `... i wonder if they think i belched wrong.'''
hazouri has made a stink about the stench in his eight months in office, demoting the city's pollution control chief, hiring eight more odor fighters, pumping up his legal staff to take polluters to court and forming a smell strike force with duval state attorney ed austin
and last tuesday, the city council passed hazouri's anti-odor bill
violations of the law can be criminal offenses punishable by up to 60 days in jail and a $500 fine, or civil cases with penalties of up to $10,000. the law also levies $50 fines for 41 other offenses
this ordinance will get the job done,'' the mayor said
the mayor blames the lion's share of odor on two pulp mills _ seminole kraft and jefferson smurfit _ and three chemical plants _ scm-glidco organics, reichhold and union camp
but the companies say they have spent millions on odor control and are being picked on
the administration has zeroed in on the pulp mills and chemical plants as the bad guys,'' said seminole kraft general manager frank lee, adding that the firm has spent $7 million at the plant to control odors. ``but there are other contributors, including landfills and sewage plants
the mayor's concept is so motherhood and apple pie. no right-thinking person would ever say, `i'm for odor.' but pulp mills have always had odor problems and always will,'' lee said. ``if the mayor has his way completely, i don't think the pulp mills and chemical companies could stay open.''
under the new law, if five people in five households complain of a smell and an inspector can validate the complaints and track the odor down, the city can impose fines
you may as well call it the lawyer's relief act of 1988,'' george robbins, president of scm-glidco, said of the new ordinance. ``what's `objectionable' odor? if you get five guys together and they complain about the smell of hamburgers coming out of a mcdonald's, is the city going to fine mcdonald's $10,000?''
a survey of college presidents indicates women may have trouble combining marriage with a climb to the top of the academic ladder
in a survey released sunday by the american council on education, 90 percent of male college presidents but only 35 percent of the female presidents said they were married
excluding nuns, priests and other members of religious orders, it said, ``the difference ... narrows somewhat. among the lay presidents, 93 percent of men but 49 percent of women were married.''
the women presidents were more likely to be divorced _ 11 percent compared with 3 percent of the men
the survey indicated the typical college president is white, male, married and 53 years old
the council sent questionnaires in 1986 to all 2,822 accredited higher education institutions and got replies back from 2,105 presidents
two hundred, or 9.5 percent, were women and 148, or 7 percent, were minorities, including 100 black presidents, 37 hispanics, eight asians and three american indians
the council's report on its survey, called ``the american college president: a contemporary profile,'' concluded, ``the image of who shall occupy the chief executive office is clearly still a traditional one.''
madeleine green, vice president of the council and director of its center for leadership development, said the data raise interesting questions that will be addressed in future studies
are family and career at the highest levels incompatible for women? are married women less likely to be selected or less likely to want a presidency?'' she asked. she also questioned whether it is harder for single men to become college presidents
other findings:
_four out of 10 women were presidents of women's colleges
_only 2 percent of predominantly white institutions were headed by blacks
_fourteen percent of the presidents were over 70 years old. only 4 percent were 40 or younger
_more than half were protestants. twenty-three percent were catholic and 3 percent jewish. thirteen percent said they were something else; 5.5 percent gave no answer
_husbands of college presidents were twice as likely to be employed as compared with wives of college presidents
_more than three quarters of the presidents held doctorates
a wild bash celebrating the 100th anniversary of the cherished cable cars 15 years ago was so much fun, san francisco is doing it again
any excuse for a party goes in this town, and the excuse monday is the centennial of the powell street lines, the picturesque junior circuit to the older california street line
the city marked 100 years of tipsy trolleys in 1973 with 11 days of parades, nightly parties, speeches and plenty of jazz. in these more austere times, the occasion will be marked by a single parade, a $40-a-plate benefit lunch for the homeless, 15,000 balloons and a giant birthday cake
presidents on the campaign trail, movie stars on location and millions of tourists and san franciscans have rumbled up and down powell during the past century, enjoying breathtaking vistas on some of the city's steepest slopes. one of the lines climbs past chinatown to fisherman's wharf, with a view of famed alcatraz island
during the years, there were spectacular accidents and annoying breakdowns, and dramatic changes as neighborhoods shifted from one ethnic group to another and buildings went up and came down
through it all, the cable cars groaned and squeaked along the hills at 9{ mph. the two powell street lines now carry about 41,000 passengers a day
you could have seen a lot of change from these cars over the past 100 years,'' says gripman phillip shaw, who's seen his share in 26 years plying powell. ``only the hills stay the same.''
shaw worked the gears and clanged the bells for presidents eisenhower and nixon, but wasn't around when soviet leader nikita khrushchev came for a ride in 1959
fellow gripman john shipman, a 15-year veteran, says the job ``never gets dull. it's the same line but every trip is different because of the people. it's an adventure. besides, i'm a skier so i love the hills. the steeper the better.''
hyde and mason streets, where the two lines run, are just right for him, with 12-degree grades in some spots
powell street is where perennial bell-ringing champ carl payne chimes through town, delighting riders with his melodies. at night, when fog creeps over the city, there isn't a more soulful sound than the muffled peals of a cable car bell
the powell-mason line opened a few months before incandescent lamps made their debut in the city at the bijou theater. today the path of the maroon, gold and white trolleys is aglow with lights
in earlier days, humphrey bogart hopped aboard the powell-hyde line as the man with the new face in ``dark passage,'' and author dashiell hammett stepped on near john's grill
the great earthquake and fire of 1906 destroyed most of the tracks and the lines' powerhouse and barn, but 27 cars outside the fire zone survived unscathed and the line was restored
the cable cars became symbols of this frontier city's eccentric and indefatigable spirit, enchanting tourists and winning the hearts of many san franciscans
when bureaucrats, bus companies and unenchanted citizens complained over the years about accidents and inefficiency, cable car boosters have joined to save the lines from destruction
the most vocal and earnest was freidel klussman, a neighborhood mover and shaker who will be remembered monday when mayor art agnos proclaims it ``freidel klussman day.''
domino's pizza promises delivery in 30 minutes or less, but some of the nation's neighborhoods are so violent the company won't let its drivers venture into them
it's not worth risking a driver for a $10 pizza,'' said robert rutick, night manager for the domino's store in irvington
at least three domino's drivers were killed last year
recent incidents such as a driver being robbed of a pizza at gunpoint and the throwing of rocks and bottles at cars led to the cutting off of night service to parts of irvington, just west of newark, where some neighborhoods are so dangerous they've never had any service
the only times we stop delivery to an area is when there have been a number of incidents,'' said rutick
delivery constitutes the majority of domino's pizza sales, with only a small amount of take-out business. many domino's outlets around the nation do not offer any eat-in service
in camden, across the delaware river from philadelphia, service is limited to only a few well-lighted areas with round-the-clock security like hospitals and the rutgers university campus, said robert lermanis, night manager for a store that serves parts of camden and burlington counties
many drivers are leery of delivering into camden because it's a high-crime area,'' lermanis said. ``we couldn't get anybody to work here if we went into camden.''
customers whose areas are cut off are told they can always come to the store to pick up a pizza, said dennis obert, security director for the domino's region that includes southern california, hawaii, arizona and nevada
one driver was killed in obert's region last year when three gang members confronted him after he delivered a pizza in san bernardino, calif
john gomez, night manager for a store in san bernardino, said the crime rate in the city 50 miles east of los angeles is ``staggering,'' even compared with his native new york city
most of my drivers are scared anyway,'' gomez said. ``but i understood myself coming from a low-income family that those people deserve the same service as the rest of the city. we just have to tell them because of the area we can't deliver at night.''
domino's policy is not shared by at least one of the national parcel delivery services, but they would not normally deliver at night
we have no company policy against not delivering to certain areas,'' said betty todd, a customer service agent at federal express' regional headquarters in memphis, tenn. ``our couriers deliver to the address on the package
our couriers don't carry money. it's not like pizza deliverers who might have $25 on them to make change.''
united parcel service offices in newark and new york city were closed sunday and officials could not be reached for comment
in chicago, domino's manager donnie crown said he won't allow drivers in certain large areas
the cops didn't tell us not to go there _ it's just common sense,'' crown said, citing incidents where delivery people had been robbed at gunpoint
ron hingst, a spokesman for the main domino's office in ann arbor, mich., said there was about one security-related incident for every 400,000 deliveries last year
domino's has a 3-year-old program of having a security director in each of its 13 regions to teach delivery people and managers ways to avoid becoming a crime victim
such advice includes being wary of telephone numbers with a fourth digit of eight or nine, which usually indicates the call was placed from a telephone booth
in some instances, police have posed as drivers to capture would-be assailants in areas where a rash of attacks and robberies have occurred
however, obert said, ``most departments don't have the time.''
two people were killed in the company's southeast region last year, said larry jerue, regional head of security in atlanta
in one case in vicksburg, miss., a delivery man was killed after being robbed of two pizzas and $4. five people apparently disposed of the body and spent the money on beer to go with the pizza, investigators said
we kind of mirror society,'' jerue said. ``violent crime is going up and, unfortunately, we've had drivers shot and killed.''
shepard nevel's opponents to be national convention delegates for michael dukakis from florida's 18th congressional district had the name recognition and experience. but nevel had the energy, the buses and the chicken salad on rye
the 28-year-old assistant dade county attorney won a trip to the democratic national convention in atlanta in july with a landslide margin in a 14-candidate field
florida democrats met in caucuses saturday in the state's 19 congressional districts to select people to represent the presidential candidates who earned delegates in the march 8 primary. the low-key atmosphere of the caucuses was in marked contrast to the excitement and media hype of super tuesday
there's not the same adrenalin and excitement about this that there was about super tuesday,'' nevel said, comparing the caucuses to the mixed doubles coming after the men's championship at wimbledon
nevel, president of the dade county young democrats club, had some secret weapons _ veteran miami beach get-out-the-vote organizer harry mildner and his father joseph nevel, a civic activist and owner of the famed wolfie's delicatessen
the number of delegates for each presidential candidate was decided by the popular vote march 8. but delegates weren't listed on that ballot
the popular vote in the 18th district _ which includes miami beach, heavily latin hialeah and a predominantly black section of miami and is represented by 87-year-old rep. claude pepper _ gave dukakis two delegates and jesse jackson one
nevel, who has been doing volunteer work in political campaigns since 1976 but had never been a delegate, faced opponents for the dukakis slots including hialeah mayor raul martinez, two state legislators, a popular former lawmakers and two city commissioners
they will win on name recognition. i'm hoping that i'll be more motivated than they are,'' nevel said as he ate breakfast early saturday
nevel had picked dukakis a year earlier. although he disagrees with dukakis on foreign policy issues such as not aiding nicaraguan contra rebels, he admires the massachusetts governor's progressive social record
nevel hosted a $30-a-head fund raiser for dukakis and co-hosted a $250 fund raiser later. he also volunteered six to eight hours a week, organizing and working telephone banks
soon after the super tuesday results were known, nevel shifted his attention to the delegate race. one problem was most of his fellow young democrats and professional colleagues live in more-suburban districts
he, miami beach activist evelyn manset and ray zeller, head of the south dade democrat club and running to be the district's one alternate, formed a coalition to run as a slate
next, nevel enlisted mildner, president of the miami beach retirees inc. with whom nevel worked closely in turning out beach voters for dukakis on march 8. they worked the telephones, contacting some 200 potential supporters
nevel and ms. manset each chartered a bus, costing some $200 each. they had paper ``palm cards'' with their slate printed up to hand out
nevel's father made up buttons and stickers for his son
and he threw in several dozen deli sandwiches
the buses began pickups at six elderly-dominated apartment buildings across miami beach at 9 a.m
a few stops later, with 45 supporters on board, nevel took the bus intercom to explain the caucus system. the supporters would be asked to produce proof they were registered democrats, fill out a form stating they supported dukakis, then proceed to an auditorium for the actual voting
at the auditorium, delegate ballots were handed out and marked. afterward, nevel's supporters got their lunch
mayer levy, a retiree from new york's east side, recalled the tammany hall era. ``they (the big-city political bosses) would get us cock-eyed on all the beer we wanted, then they told us to vote early and vote often.''
lillian alderson, also from new york, said she liked nevel, but she also liked the free lunch. ``i waited an hour for the bus. shows how greedy we are,'' she said, laughing
then the results came in. nevel won in a landslide with 92 votes, 68 ahead of his nearest competitor. ms. manset and zeller also won
nevel reflected: ``when i think back to what a longshot dukakis was a year ago and then to what a longshot i was, and now to be going to the convention...''
a moderate earthquake rocked northwestern greece and southern albania, causing panic and some damage but no injuries, authorities said sunday
a spokeswoman for the athens seismological institute said the quake measured 5.2 on the richter scale and was centered on the western albanian coast, 236 miles northwest of athens
it struck at 9:35 p.m. saturday
the official albanian news agency ata said the quake was felt in seven albanian districts and caused unspecified damage
the earth really moved. most people stayed indoors, but some panicked and ran into the streets expecting a second quake,'' said a police spokesman on the western resort island of corfu
the richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs.an earthquake of 5 can cause considerable damage and 6 severe damage
the navy's trident ii program to build a newer, more deadly submarine-launched missile is ``sound, stable and disciplined,'' according to a review released sunday by the house armed services committee
in rare praise for a u.s. nuclear weapons program, the democratic-controlled panel said the trident ii, scheduled to enter service in about 18 months, appears to be on time and under budget
the other programs we've looked at had a variety of problems, so this is kind of a man-bites-dog story, but it is important to give credit when it is due,'' said rep. les aspin, d-wis., chairman of the panel
the committee's report was the latest in a series of studies on u.s. nuclear weapons programs, but it was the first in which the panel praised the pentagon
the trident ii, also known as the d-5, is a submarine-launched weapon that will be put aboard trident submarines starting next year. it has a longer range and is more accurate than the trident i weapon it will replace
although the trident weapons comprise a growing portion of the u.s. nuclear arsenal, they have generally escaped the controversy that has enveloped president reagan's programs to build new land-based nuclear missiles and long-range bombers. after a series of cost overruns early in the trident program, few problems have surfaced
the committee's review singled out for praise the navy's strategic systems program office (sspo), saying it has ``a well-run program.''
we've some elements of what the sspo is doing in other programs, but not as many as we're seeing in this one program,'' aspin said
for instance, aspin said, the office is managing weapons-building programs longer and has more wide-ranging authority than other pentagon offices
the trident ii will cost at least $36 billion, but the eventual cost is unclear because the navy hasn't finally decided how many of the trident missile-firing subs it will build
congress has already authorized 15 of the boats, which each carry a dozen missiles that can carry up to eight warheads each
the trident ii missile is now being flight-tested at cape canaveral, fla. eight of the nine scheduled tests have been finished and the results show seven successful shots, one failure, and one delay. the failure has delayed the program, but there is enough flexibility in the schedule so that the missile is still expected to be completed on time, the report said
while the house report praised the navy, it said that technical difficulties have been discovered in the inertial measurement unit, the part of the guidance system that directs the weapon to its target
aspin has been sharply critical of the air force because of inertial measurement unit problems in the mx nuclear-tipped missile, but the situation is not as serious in the case of the trident, he said. the two weapons use different units
more than 12.3 million cars, trucks, vans and motorcycles valued at $52 billion were stolen over a 13-year period, the federal government estimated sunday
after recovery of about 65 percent of them, losses were estimated at $29 billion in 1985 dollars
insurance payments reduced actual losses to vehicle owners to an estimated $16.1 billion, according to an analysis of the bureau of justice statistics national crime surveys for the years 1973 through 1985
the number of thefts per 1,000 registered vehicles fell 33 percent over the surveyed period, from nine to just six, the bureau concluded in an analysis of its semiannual surveys of more than 40,000 households nationwide
over the period, the number of estimated vehicle thefts per 1,000 households also declined, by 21 percent, from 13.3 in 1973 to 10.5 in 1985
in addition to the vehicle thefts during the period, there were an estimated 7 million attempted thefts, said bjs director steven schlesinger. about 64 percent of those were not reported to police, he said, and 13 percent of the actual vehicle thefts also went unreported
half of the thefts involved a loss of $2,455 or more before recoveries and insurance payments. about 10 percent involved losses of $10,000 or more
the vehicle stolen in 76 percent of the cases surveyed was a car. the rest were trucks, vans and motorcycles
in 7 percent of the completed thefts, the vehicle was in a garage at home. thefts most often took place at night and in parking lots, on the street or near the victim's home
the most likely to be victimized by car theft were blacks, hispanics, households headed by people under age 25, people in multiple-dwelling units, central city residents and low-income households
those least likely to be victims were people 55 years and older, homeowners and rural residents
stu smith, bureau spokesman, said the report was based on a new computer analysis of the extensive crime surveys the statistics bureau conducts every six months
he said officials believe the statistics are more accurate than police reports because they are based on actual interviews with people in the households surveyed and cover crimes not reported to the police
renato salvatori, the former lifeguard who became a star of the italian cinema, died sunday at his home in rome after a fighting a liver disease for a year and a half. he was 55
the italian news agency ansa said salvatori, who had retired from acting, suffered from cirrhosis of the liver, the same disease that afflicted his father
salvatori was working as a lifeguard on an italian beach in 1951 when he was discovered by director luciano emmer and given a role in ``the children of piazza di spagna.''
that movie began a film career that included, among many others, dino risi's ``poor but pretty,'' luchino viscoti's ``rocco and his brothers'' and francesco rosi's ``the peddlers.''
salvatori will be buried wednesday in the tomb of his family in the cemetery of querceto. he is survived by two children
it was strictly a borderline affair, but the newlyweds didn't seem to mind. after all, the bride hails from arkansas and the groom from texas
saturday night's wedding of gayle nichols, 31, and wayne burkland, 40, took place in front of the downtown post office, which straddles the border between the two states
a couple of steps down the aisle, er, sidewalk, and the knot would have been tied in texas
both burkland and his new wife are postal employees
we always wanted to get married here,'' burkland said after the ceremony
under the stars,'' his bride added
ms. nichols is a native of el dorado, ark., 90 miles east of this border town. burkland hails from new boston, texas, 25 miles to the west
miller county, ark., justice of the peace h.q. russell was unflappable as he officiated. russell said it was the third wedding he's performed on the state line
soon, boston cab riders will be able to ``reach out and touch someone'' even while sitting in traffic
nynex mobile communications corp. will begin installing the first 20 car phone units in independent taxi operators association cabs monday, nynex vice president peter harrigan said
another firm, downer communications, also reported similar negotations with the red &amp; white cab association and the boston cab co
with a half-hour trip facing him, we think that a stockbroker on his way to work may well want to place a call to hong kong on his way to execute an early trade,'' said president charles w. downer
the cost of a two-minute local call will start at $3.50 to $3.70, well above the 10-cent charge on a boston street pay phone. and long distance connections will cost more. charges will be payable by credit card
nynex and downer plan to pay cab operators a percentage of the local call charge. the cabs will be marked so prospective riders can tell they are equipped with telephones, which will carry only outgoing calls
similar telephones were tried last year in a few british cabs, and several were installed in ``black car'' taxis in new york city, which are barred from picking up fares on the street
each unit costs $1,500 to $2,000, but downer believes they could make a profit on a few calls a day
key west has the best blow-hards in the business, judging from results of the island's 26th annual conch shell blowing contest
tooters from 3 to 58 competed saturday, and when the noise died down, the hometown favorites had swept the contest over visiting tourists
as legend has it, conch blowing dates back hundreds of years in the florida keys, to the days when calusa indians and pirates who lived here used the shells for communication. a toot was a signal of survival or distress
the best blowers of the tightly coiled shells, all from key west, were joshua gabbard, 5; christopher vargas, 8; jeffrey roberson, 11 and steve hoyt, 35
conch, a food staple from northern brazil to bermuda, is found throughout the caribbean and lower florida keys. they are most popular in fritters, chowders and salads
the race for the white house focuses for a week on wisconsin, as democrat jesse jackson rolls into the traditionally liberal-voting state on the heels of a stunning triumph in next-door michigan and michael dukakis urgently needs to ignite some excitement
george bush looked on the verge of sweeping the republican primary almost by default as bob dole's campaign withered
wisconsin's primary is a week from tuesday, on april 5, and the state has an importance outstripping its 81 democratic delegates at stake
connecticut's primary tuesday was the next event on the presidential calender. but bush, in another of his ``home states,'' had it sewn up in the gop balloting. dukakis' strength in a state that borders his home of massachusetts reduced the stakes there for the other democrats
for democrat richard gephardt, the road to the white house may have ended in milwaukee, where he spoke to state democrats late saturday night knowing that his poor third-place finish in michigan hadn't come close to the showing he had needed to sustain a credible candidacy
he went home to washington by private jet, accompanied only by his wife and a few aides, to consider his next move
all things considered, i'd rather be back in des moines,'' said gephardt, who won iowa's lead-off caucuses seven weeks ago but was unable to capitalize on it elsewhere
aides said beforehand that without a victory in michigan he would drop out and seek re-election to congress from missouri
wisconsin presents a contest of major importance for the two other democrats, paul simon and albert gore jr
gore was investing heavily in television ads in wisconsin and has already been on the air in the state for a week. the tennessee senator has yet to break out of single digits since the campaign left the south, and his strategists were hoping the state would return him to the top ranks of contenders just before the giant new york primary on april 19, when 255 democratic delegates are at stake
i need your help and i'm here to ask for it,'' gore said as he stumped in the state over the weekend
for simon, wisconsin offered a perhaps final chance to get back into the race. his hopes turn on whether the state, whose history of liberal primary winners includes eugene mccarthy in 1968 and george mcgovern in 1972, will embrace simon's campaign as the unapologetic, traditional liberal
there was little sign that it would, however, as simon was out of money and jackson emerged from michigan with a major win as the liberal candidate. although wisconsin is only 4 percent black, jackson was likely to exceed the 10 percent he gained in the state in 1984
jackson's virtual 2-1 victory in michigan over dukakis was a strong blow to the massachusetts governor, heretofore the frontrunner, who many democrats had been depicting as the inevitable nominee once the race moved into the ethnic and industrial northern states where he should do well
that argument of inevitability became harder to sustain after a third place finish in illinois and a distant second in michigan
in some sense, it's a lot of poetry,'' jackson said in milwaukee, the results still coming in from michigan where george wallace won 16 years earlier. ``it's a lot of history. we also have the numbers, and it's a lot of reality.''
republican dole had looked to wisconsin as a chance to recoup, and he stumped the state last week. but he also was hinting he may quit before wisconsin's primary and said bush's nomination was ``a foregone conclusion.''
the only recent poll, conducted by the milwaukee journal 11 days ago, gave bush the lead over dole by better than 2-1. among democrats, dukakis had 38 percent to jackson's 30 percent, with the rest far behind
wisconsin's primary is an open event, so republicans could cross over to vote in the more competitive democratic race. it has been unkind to frontrunners, as walter mondale lost here to gary hart in a 1984 popular vote that did not award delegates
samuel c. koupchik, a fixture in the massachusetts statehouse for generations and the basis for a character in the novel ``the last hurrah,'' has died at the age of 89
koupchik, who died friday after suffering a heart attack, spent his days around the document room of the statehouse, handing out legislative calendars to reporters and lobbyists, working as a runner for lobbyists and occasionally giving free political advice
he was an honorary member of both the house and the senate, where a memorial service was planned monday
a native of russia, he began working as a 10-year-old errand boy for a city political leader. he went on to a series of city and state jobs _ including interpreter, ferry worker, constable and member of the boston election, street and law departments
he spent 25 years as a mail carrier for the registry of motor vehicles and had been an aide to the late gov. james michael curley
in the novel ``the last hurrah'' by edwin o'connor, the character of ditto was based on koupchik
sammy represented a bygone era of politics when loyalty was the most valued of all principles,'' house speaker george keverian said through a spokesman. ``he like to tell and repeated often stories recalling acts of loyalty by the political kingpins of his day. he'll be missed. there are no more sammy koupchiks.''
koupchik was never married and is survived by six nephews and a niece
nicaraguan exiles bowed their heads in a special outdoors palm sunday mass and prayed that last week's contra-sandinista cease-fire pact is not sandinista treachery
the general feeling is confusion, what will happen now in nicaragua,'' said roberto serrano, an engineer who has worked as a medley wine importer since leaving his homeland. ``we have to wait and see.''
he and more than 300 nicaraguan exiles gathered in ronselli park in this nicaraguan exile enclave, to pray with exiled monsignor pablo antonio vega
we want peace in nicaragua, but we don't believe we have enough guarantees to go back, for we believe the sandinistas don't like to be at peace inside nicaragua,'' said eduardo salgado
the nicaragua civic union, which represents some nicaragua exile groups, called the mass to show solidarity, salgado said
the gathering in this western dade county city, home of ``little managua,'' came a day after about 200 peace demonstrators applauded the cease-fire pact in downtown miami and a handful of demonstrators blasted it outside a miami hotel where contra leaders were holding closed-door meetings
under the agreement, which declares a cease-fire until june 1, the contras have agreed not to accept any more u.s. military aid. in return, the leftist sandinistas promised a gradual amnesty for contras and unrestricted freedom of expression that would allow them a role in nicaragua's political process
no matter what we (as individuals) believe in, there's only one ideal that prevails _ to keep on the struggle of the nicaraguan people until the soviets and communist cubans leave nicaragua,'' said manuel molina. ``the sandinistas are no problem to us because they are a very small group of criminals. but the soviet force, that's a whole different ball game.''
the peace pact also has divided the 54-member nicaraguan resistance assembly. in a special six-hour session saturday, it created a commission to monitor its five directors when they resume negotiations with the sandinistas this week
the assembly, which represents nine nicaraguan political opposition groups, was formed last year and has the right to overrule its directors
assembly leaders said the 60-day cease-fire pact, signed wednesday in nicaragua by directors adolfo calero and aristides sanchez, is only the first step in ending the seven-year civil war
if we don't get (freedom) through negotiations, we'll get it through war,'' calero said sunday on nbc's ``meet the press.''
we will not disband and we will not lay down our weapons,'' he said
at saturday's meeting, former nicaraguan vice president silvio arguello said the formation of the negotiation watchdog committee was not meant to rebuke the directors who completed the cease-fire pact. its purpose will be to see that exiles' hopes to reclaim a life in nicaragua are not compromised
however, arguello said the contra directors have lost touch with the exile community
a man wielding an ax and knife burst into a worship service sunday and seriously wounded three congregation members, police said
the attacker slit a woman's throat, sliced another woman's hand and bashed a man over the head with the ax, according to lbc, a london radio station. he then sped away in a car and set fire to his home before he was arrested, police said
police were unsure of a motive in the attack on the pentecostal service in central reading, 35 miles west of london
about 20 worshipers, some in blood-splattered clothes, escaped harm as they dived to the floor, witnesses said
worshiper golburne vaughan said the attack came without warning after the group had gathered at a community center for the church of god and christ united service
suddenly, a man came in carrying an ax and went straight to one man, hitting him on the head,'' he said. ``most of the people were middle-aged, and we all dived under chairs and tried to hide. there was blood everywhere as three people were chopped with the ax or stabbed. it was all over very quickly.''
a 54-year-old woman whose throat was slit was reported in critical condition at a local hospital. the other victims, a 31-year-old man and a 30-year-old woman, were reported in stable condition. authorities did not identify them immediately
police were questioning a 46-year-old suspect, said inspector jim reilly of the thames valley police force. the man had not been charged
reilly said he didn't know if the attacker knew his victims
the friends of a missionary slain in south africa say his commitment to justice and dignity will be remembered best where it is needed most
the rev. wayne steinert is not dead,'' menardo gomez, bishop of the lutheran church in el salvador, said at a memorial service here saturday at riverside community church
he lives in africa, swaziland. in paraguay and in el salvador, where we will remember him and follow his example, wayne peter steinert is present.''
steinert, 41, was shot and killed march 2 in piet retief, a city just across the border of swaziland in the south african province of transvaal, while traveling to meet a group of church members in lesotho. a south african was held for questioning, but few details of the incident have come to light
the rev. stephen lusk, minister of riverside and a friend of steinert's, said steinert was a victim of the anger and paranoia of those who fear social change
steinert was a minister of the united church of christ and the disciples of christ denominations and served as an intern at riverside more than a decade ago. since then, he worked at missions in paraguay and el salvador before being assigned to swaziland with his wife, terri, less than a year ago
gomez, one of four salvadorans at the service, called steinert a ``martyr, a hero of faith, a soldier of christ.''
the first man to invoke colorado's ``make my day'' defense in a shooting, arguing he was protecting his family, has been convicted in a separate case of murdering his estranged wife and wounding her boyfriend
david guenther, 35, sat emotionless saturday when adams county district court judge harlan bockman read guilty verdicts for first-degree murder, attempted first-degree murder and first-degree assault
bockman set a may 6 sentencing date. a person convicted of first-degree murder in colorado must serve 40 years in prison before becoming eligible for parole. prosecutors said earlier they would not seek the death penalty
it made my day,'' co-prosecutor bruce levin said of the verdict, referring to the so-called ``make my day'' law which allows residents to use deadly force in their homes against intruders. it was nicknamed after a line in a clint eastwood film in which a cop invites a criminal to ``make my day'' and give the cop an excuse to shoot
guenther was the first person to invoke that defense, saying he could not be charged with the fatal shooting of a neighbor and the wounding of two other people outside his home in 1986 because he was protecting his family
guenther was acquitted but that was overturned by the colorado supreme court. the charges were reinstated, and a jury acquitted guenther in the second trial last oct. 22, but on the basis of self-defense rather than the ``make my day'' rule
on march 1, 1987, guenther shot and killed his wife, pamela, 30, and wounded her boyfriend, stanley stinson, outside a commerce city restaurant
the guenthers' two children, christopher, 13, and jennifer, 11, saw the shootings and were key prosecution witnesses along with stinson
when the trial opened tuesday, both sides agreed there was no question that guenther killed his wife and wounded stinson. at issue was whether he acted with deliberation, as the prosecution contended, or whether he fired eight shots in the ``heat of passion'' when he saw his wife kissing stinson
prosecutor tim meinert reminded jurors of a pattern of threats and violence by guenther against his estranged wife, who took her children and left him about a month before she was killed
testimony showed he took his wife hostage at their home one week before her death, releasing her unharmed after a standoff with police that lasted several hours
the jury deliberated for three hours
stinson said of the verdict: ``they gave this guy exactly what he deserved. i can get a good night's sleep now. i haven't slept for about a year.''
amiram nir, prime minister yitzhak shamir's counterterrorism adviser involved in the iran-contra affair, has resigned, the government announced sunday
the government also announced the resignation of yosef harmelin, head of the shin bet secret service for more than 11 years
shamir accepted nir's resignation two weeks ago and it will take effect on april 1, the government announcement said
the government gave no reasons for the resignation. media reports said the reasons were political and not related to the iran-contra affair
nir, a former journalist, was appointed by labor party leader shimon peres, who became prime minister after the inconclusive elections in 1984
in january 1986, nir became involved in the iran operation and took over from three israeli middlemen _ foreign ministry director david kimche, businessmen yakov nimrodi and al schwimmer
before nir's involvement, the three mediated a secret 1985 arms deal between iran and the united states in exchange for the freedom of u.s. hostages held by pro-iranian shiite fundamentalists in lebanon
israel then shipped 508 u.s.-made tow anti-tank missiles and 18 hawk anti-aircraft missiles to iran. the united states took over the shipments in february 1986 but continued to use israel as a transfer point for the arms
in testimony before congressional investigators last july, former u.s. national security council aide lt. col. oliver north listed nir as a main mover behind the weapons deals
north alleged nir was one of the first to propose diverting funds from the arms deals to nicaragua's anti-government rebels, the contras
north recently pleaded innocent in federal court in washington, d.c. to a series of charges in connection with the iran-contra affair
since news of the iranian deals broke, israel has mantained that it only acted in cooperation with the united states and denied any knowledge of alleged diversion of funds to the contras
nir has been sought for questioning by special u.s. prosecutor lawrence e. walsh. in exchange, israel has insisted on an agreement that nir be granted immunity from prosecution
shamir had planned to dismiss nir in 1986 under a power-sharing agreement with peres
peres, who is currently foreign minister, served as prime minister from 1984-1986 under the accord with shamir's right-wing likud bloc. shamir took over as prime minister in october 1986
news reports said that shamir could not fire nir in 1986 because he feared his dismissal might be interpreted in the united states as punishment for nir's involvement in the weapons' deals
harmelin, 65, joined israel's secret service soon after the jewish state came into being in 1948
he held various intelligence posts before becoming chief of the secret service in 1964
harmelin was responsible for building israel's intelligence network in the west bank and gaza strip after israel captured these lands from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war
he left the post in 1974 to become israel's ambassador in iran and south africa. in july 1986 he was called back to the secret service as a temporary replacement for avraham shalom-ahituv, who resigned after the so-called shin bet affair
in the affair, shin bet agents were accused of fabricating evidence to conceal their role in the beating deaths of two palestinians who hijacked an israeli passenger bus in april 1984. apart</head>
the baby m surrogate motherhood case is to draw to a close in a courtroom here monday, but elsewhere problems will be just beginning for two people who look and act like mary beth whitehead and william stern
by coincidence, producers are to film a scene for a upcoming two-part tv miniseries on the baby m case in a new jersey turnpike rest area at the same time the real-life litigants are to be in court for a visitation hearing
the hearing was ordered by the state supreme court to determine how much mrs. whitehead may visit baby m, now legally known as melissa stern
to some extent it's a sad coincidence,'' said ilene berg, executive producer of the film, which is scheduled to be broadcast in may on abc. ``it's sad that this is still not resolved, that it's never going to be perfect.''
the producers were scheduled to film one of the early meetings of stern and mrs. whitehead, now known as mrs. whitehead-gould after her second marriage, at a rest area about 8 miles south of the bergen county courthouse
the two used to meet there before they would drive together to a clinic in new york city where mrs. whitehead-gould was inseminated with stern's sperm as part of a $10,000 surrogate contract
the scene is part of a four-hour miniseries that covers the introduction of the sterns and whiteheads, the birth of baby m, the surrogate mother's flight to florida with the child after she decided she couldn't give up the baby, and the lower court custody trial which mrs. whitehead-gould lost
at the end of the film, an update will tell of the state supreme court decision that reversed most of the lower court ruling, granting custody of the baby to stern but restoring mrs. whitehead-gould's parental rights
the highway rest area scene is the last to be filmed. the rest of the movie was shot in a van nuys, calif., soundstage where producers built a replica of the bergen county courtroom where the baby m case was played out
ms. berg said the coincidence of the new jersey filming on the same day as the visitation hearing was a bit of good fortune for the miniseries
it shows, if anything, that our movie is still very timely,'' she said
since neither side in the baby m dispute agreed to take part in the movie, producers wrote the script from court documents and news reports. they said they tried to take no sides in the battle, letting the facts speak for themselves
i expect people will be arguing about this after it (the movie) is over,'' said producer gordon freedman
actress jo beth williams, seen in ``the big chill'' and ``the day after,'' plays mrs. whitehead-gould, while actor john shea plays stern and soap opera actress robin strasser plays stern's wife, elizabeth
hill street blues' bruce weitz plays the surrogate mother's first husband, richard whitehead; actress anne jackson plays baby m's legal guardian, lorraine abraham; and dabney coleman of ``the slap maxwell story'' plays the sterns' attorney, gary skoloff
ms. williams said she studied for the part by reading court documents and newspaper clippings, and watching television news reports
in playing mrs. whitehead-gould, the actress said, she found that the surrogate mother was neither a victim nor a heroine
it's difficult to put a single label on her,'' ms. williams said. ``she's a woman who was put in a very difficult situation. some of what mary beth did was impulsive. but it was out of desperation
i feel very strongly for both sides of this story. they both have been through tremendous pain.'' monday</head>
four consecutive days of torrential rain left at least 18 people dead and forced the evacuation of 55,000 residents of the buenos aires-la plata area, officials said sunday
the latest victim was a 4-year-old boy from villa soldati who was swept away by floodwaters sunday, authorities said. weather forecasters said the heavy rains that have pounded buenos aires and central argentina since thursday would continue monday
families have been forced to flee to the roofs of their homes to escape floodwaters in some low-lying areas. firefighters and police have used boats, makeshift rafts and horses to help evacuate families to temporary shelters in schools, sports clubs and office buildings
the dead included seven children who drowned and two women electrocuted while crossing flooded streets where live cables had fallen. 6th pvs, ``it is...'</note>
anti-apartheid clergyman allan boesak said sunday that if he is killed, the government and police should come under suspicion
over the last week there have been more death threats,'' said boesak, leader of the mixed-race branch of the dutch reformed church and president of the world alliance of reformed churches
i want the world to know the light of suspicion should fall on the south african government and the police if something like that should happen,'' he said at a news conference
one doesn't say these things to create an atmosphere of martyrdom. it has happened before in this country. people have died mysteriously.''
capt. j.l. barnard, a spokesman for national police headquarters in pretoria, said boesak had made ``a totally unfair, untrue and malicious statement.''
it is another example of how untested, unsubstantiated, one-sided allegations are made in public in a bid to discredit the south african police as well as the south african government,'' he said
boesak said volunteer student guards had seen a police car drive by his home early tuesday. a passenger in the back seat pointed a gun out the window, but the guards shined lights and the car sped away, he said
this is a very sinister development,'' boesak said. he said police later denied dispatching a car to the area
barnard said he could not comment on the facts of boesak's allegations about the car
boesak and other south african church leaders have vowed to take a more confrontational approach since the government banned the 17 leading anti-apartheid groups last month. among the protesting clergymen are anglican archbishop desmond tutu, winner of the 1984 nobel peace prize; and the rev. frank chikane, head of the south african council of churches
authorities arrested 25 of the church leaders feb. 29 when they tried to march to parliament with a petition protesting the bans. the government also banned a new committee for the defense of democracy set up to take over activities of the outlawed organizations
boesak on sunday lamented statements by the white branch of the country's dutch reformed church saying he and tutu don't represent the church
the white dutch reformed church is saying to the state, `these people are not the church and do not represent the church; therefore, when you act against them, you are not acting against the church,''' said boesak. ``once you create that kind of atmosphere, almost everybody out there who is angry with us could feel justified in threatening our lives because the church said they were not acting against people of god.''
boesak's news conference was attended by a delegation from the world alliance. it had come to express solidarity with south african clergymen who are challenging the government and its apartheid segregation policies
leaders of the alliance, based in geneva, said they represent 164 churches with a worldwide membership of 70 million. sunday's cape town delegation included a swiss minister, edmond perret, general secretary of the aliance; and joachim guhrt, president of the reformed churches of west germany
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
police raids that began last week have netted at least six people suspected of spying in this country for the soviet kgb, a leading newspaper said sunday
the bonn-based newspaper die welt, quoting unidentified security sources, said the suspects include russian emigres placed in west germany by the soviet intelligence and secret police agency
die welt said one suspect was arrested in switzerland and that the others were nabbed by west german federal police
authorities have not confirmed the report. it was to appear in die welt's monday editions and was telexed in advance to other news organizations
other west german newspapers reported sunday that eight to 15 suspected spies had been caught in raids that began thursday
federal officials have refused to release details on the operation until it is over. gerhard boeden, president of the watchdog federal agency known as the ministry for the protection of the constitution, was quoted in the mass-publication bild am sonntag sunday newspaper as saying the investigation was open
he also said communist espionage has increased since relations between the kremlin and western countries have thawed
in times when political tensions are relaxed, eastern intelligence agencies ... become much more active,'' boeden said in a sunday radio interview
he said most of the communist agents working in west germany have been sent by east germany
newspapers, quoting security sources, said the suspects include government employees with access to key information. among reported suspects were an engineer with access to top-secret plans for the nato defense alliance's jaeger jet fighter
gov. evan mecham, attempting to convince the arizona senate that his $80,000 loan from a protocol fund was on the up-and-up, suggests that if he hadn't borrowed the money others might have spent it
you know, money is like honey,'' mecham said during his impeachment trial. ``honey attracts bees and money attracts people
people heard there was money, and they came in with ideas to spend it. `can we do this with it? can we do that with it?'''
he said during his testimony last week he had the best idea for the funds that had been raised by his inaugural committee to pay off campaign debts. when a state law blocked use of the money for that purpose, mecham said he proposed the protocol fund
other governors had such funds, he said, and the purpose was to make sure the governor ``wouldn't have to go into the hole'' for incidental expenses
for instance, he said, the fund could pay for his wife, florence, to accompany him to official events out of town
it was my understanding this was to keep me from having to spend my own personal money for things for my office,'' said the governor
he conceded there were items for which he knew he couldn't use the fund: politics and living expenses. but he said he never suspected that loaning the money to his own car dealership was forbidden. and he never considered the fund public property
i never heard the words discussed, `public funds,''' said the first-term republican governor, the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades
in the second of three impeachment charges, mecham is accused of misusing state funds by borrowing the $80,000. earlier in the trial, senators heard evidence on a charge that he tried to halt an investigation of an alleged death threat by a member of his staff
on both charges, the governor's basic defense is ignorance of the facts. on the first count, he contends he was never fully informed of details of the alleged threat and had no idea a crime might have been committed. on the second count, he argues he was never told the fund had become public money and wasn't aware that borrowing the $80,000 might violate conditions of a legal agreement for its use
he said he received instructions about the money from william long, his inaugural chairman, who signed an agreement with the maricopa county attorney's office to avoid a lawsuit over use of the proceeds from mecham's inaugural ball
mr. long said, `we have gone through all of this rigamarole and you can spend it for any damned thing that you want, except you can't spend it for politics or living expenses,''' mecham testified
long is ill and has not testified. he submitted an affidavit that seemed to support mecham's position
at no time was governor mecham informed that these monies were a gift to the state of arizona or a gift to anyone other than evan mecham ... to be used for the lawful purposes which had been agreed upon,'' long said
with the trial entering its fifth week, the senate has yet to take up the charge considered most critical, the allegation that he concealed a $350,000 campaign loan from developer barry wolfson. it is the only one of the three counts which also is the basis of a criminal felony case set for trial april 21
meanwhile, the governor continues to campaign for re-election in a recall election scheduled for may 17. a poll released sunday showed that mecham would still be one of the front runners if the election were held now, but 54 percent of voters said mecham would be ``unacceptable'' as governor. the poll was commissioned by the arizona republic and kpnx-tv
here are the latest unofficial results in the democratic presidential caucuses in michigan

