jesse jackson's victory in michigan forces the democratic party to take a more serious look at his presidential bid and increases his chances of winning in the high-stakes new york primary, political analysts said sunday
jackson defeated front-runner michael dukakis by almost 2-1 in michigan's primary-like caucuses saturday, infusing new momentum into an already strong campaign that is within striking distance of first place in the national delegate count
there are still some in the political establishment who think 1988 is an inevitable replay of 1984,'' said ann lewis, a democratic strategist and an informal adviser to jackson's campaign. ``the day after michigan a new world has dawned.''
with returns from 94 percent of the voting sites in michigan, jackson had 107,689 or 55 percent to 55,337 or 28 percent for dukakis. jackson won enormous majorities in detroit. in the 1st congressional district, for example, jackson beat dukakis 25,416 to 1,809. in the 13th, the margin was 17,725 to 1,539
jackson, treated as a fringe candidate in 1984, has won in eight states, michigan, alabama, georgia, louisiana, mississippi, virginia, south carolina, alaska, and puerto rico's non-binding contest. the victories are forcing the party to re-examine the theory that a black cannot be nominated for president in 1988
jesse is running to win the nomination,'' ms. lewis said. ``what does the democratic party give him? the morning after michigan he earns the right, it's not what we give him.''
paul maslin, pollster for illinois sen. paul simon's campaign, said jackson's michigan victory and possible wins in wisconsin and new york could give him the most national delegates
a real extraordinary endgame is presenting itself to the democratic party ... they have to be seriously thinking about the prospect of a jackson nomination,'' maslin said
jackson's win also puts greater pressure on dukakis, who has failed to win in major contests in illinois and michigan, and faces a serious challenge in new york, which has 255 delegates at stake in its april 19th primary
new york is going to be a major test,'' ms. lewis said. ``michigan greatly raises the stakes in new york.''
the stakes could not be more critical,'' said maslin. ``he (dukakis) can't just finish second to jesse jackson. he can't say i'm the leading white candidate. it's not going to work this year.''
a new york daily news poll published sunday shows dukakis favored by 45 percent of the 528 democrats surveyed to 29 percent for jackson. the poll, conducted between monday, march 21 and thursday, march 24, had a margin for error of plus or minus 4.5 percentage points
however, new york gov. mario cuomo has said that if two or three candidates are left in the democratic race prior to the primary, jackson has a chance of winning
missouri rep. richard gephardt was expected to drop out of the race to run for re-election to his congressional seat
in addition, a marist college institute for public opinion poll found that 57 percent of 459 democratic voters surveyed earlier this month gave jackson a favorable rating, to 30 percent unfavorable. the same survey, conducted in january, gave jackson a 44 percent favorable rating to 41 percent unfavorable
new york is a fairly volatile state,'' said david garth, a media consultant who is working for tennessee sen. albert gore jr.'s campaign. ``there is a strong potential jewish vote.''
in the marist college survey, 36 percent of the jewish voters gave jackson a favorable rating, an increase from 17 percent in january. forty-three percent gave jackson an unfavorable rating to 62 percent in january. the poll has a margin of error of 5 percent
garth said jackson can win in new york because ``dukakis has proven he can't stop him.'' but the consultant said the party has become more conservative in recent years
new yorkers have generally moved from the left to much more moderate democrats. they got to have somebody to win the election,'' he said. ``it used to be the ndc (national democratic committee) was `novemeber doesn't count.' the old new york is not the same. it's a wide-open race.''
president hussain muhammad ershad announced a new 32-member cabinet sunday, replacing prime minister mizanur rahman choudhury but retaining other aides in important positions
named to succeed choudhury was deputy prime minister maudud ahmed, a british-trained lawyer, who also will have the industries ministry. political observers said choudhury may become speaker of the 300-member parliament
foreign minister humayun rasheed choudhury and finance minister maj. gen. abdul munem will remain in their posts in the cabinet, known as the council of ministers
cabinet changes had been expected after ershad's jatiya party won the march 3 elections that were boycotted by the major opposition groups. jatiya won 251 seats in parliament
kazi jafar ahmed, a political advisor to the president, was promoted to deputy prime minister replacing maudud ahmed. the two other deputy prime ministers are shah moazem hussain, who also heads the rural development and local government ministries, and abdul matin who is in charge of the home ministry
political analysts said no major shifts were expected in ershad's policies of non-alignment and a free-market economy
alliances headed by two major opposition leaders, sheik hasina and khalida zia, have organized scores of demonstrations since nov. 10, demanding that ershad resign
ershad, a 58-year-old former army general, declared a state of emergency on dec. 6 to curb the anti-government protests. he seized power in a coup in march 1982, asssumed the presidency in 1983 and was elected president in 1986
residents of a neighborhood here say they are afraid to park on the streets after an arsonist torched as many as seven cars last week
this whole world is going kaput,'' said one resident, josephine piotrowski
the arsonist burned five cars and is believed to be responsible for at least two other car fires since march 23, said david kessinger, the city's deputy fire marshal. all of the fires occurred in the same north city neighborhood, he said, but who started them and why are unknown
he finds a car that's unlocked _ bam,'' kessinger said
larry graves said he woke up about 1:30 a.m. saturday as firefighters were putting out the flames that destroyed his two-door 1965 mercedes-benz
you go to bed, your car's sitting there fine. then you get woken up and your car's a lump of nothing,'' he said
egypt on sunday welcomed the scheduled return to the middle east of secretary of state george p. shultz, who will be trying to gain support for a u.s. plan aimed at settling the arab-israeli conflict
foreign minister esmat abdel-meguid told reporters egypt hopes shultz's visit will ``add momentum to the peace process and to the search for a lasting, just peace.''
shultz is scheduled to arrive in jerusalem on april 3 for talks with israeli leaders and then go to jordan, egypt, syria and saudi arabia before returning to washington april 8
he was on a shuttle tour of the region earlier this month and presented the leaders of israel, syria, jordan and egypt with the u.s. proposal
egypt is the only arab nation that has diplomatic relations with israel
syria and israel have expressed strong reservations about the american plan. jordan has not given a definite reply
the plan calls for an international conference as early as may 1 to launch talks on a type of self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinians living in the israeli-occupied west bank of the jordan river and gaza strip
negotiations on the final status of the occupied territories would start next december
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir is opposed to an international conference, which would include the five permanent members of the u.n. security council _ america, the soviet union, china, britain and france. shamir has said such a conference could attempt to force israel to make concessions that would jeopardize the nation's security

