the sandinista government freed 100 political prisoners sunday under an amnesty program, fulfilling the first part of a cease-fire pact with nicaraguan rebels
interior minister tomas borge called the gesture ``possibly the beginning of the end of the war.''
tearful family members embraced their loved ones who were released from the zona franca jail on the outskirts of managua. but amid the joy was an air of doubt
they say i don't have anything to fear,'' said feliz pedro chavaria gomez, 32, holding a plastic sack containing his belongings. ``i'm happy, but i hope it doesn't fail.''
chavaria said he was arrested in 1980 and charged with being a counter-revolutionary
cesar augusto flores mireando, 25, was arrested more than two years ago in managua. ``the majority of the peasants here are innocent,'' he said
the release of the prisoners was the first step in an amnesty plan the sandinistas agreed to wednesday when they signed a cease-fire accord with leaders of the u.s.-backed rebels known as contras. the sides declared a truce march 21 and a a 60-day cease-fire is to begin april 1
in another development, president daniel ortega suggested the united nations send a multi-national peacekeeping force to the nicaraguan-honduran border to stabilize the area
of the prisoners freed sunday, 24 were workers arrested for joining illegal strikes
the release was ordered under an amnesty law the national assembly approved by a margin of 82-2 saturday night. the law could result in the release of about 3,300 political prisoners jailed since the sandinistas seized power in a 1979 revolution that overthrew right-wing president anastasio somoza
sandinistas hold 61 seats in the 96-member assembly
according to the legislation, another undisclosed number of contras taken prisoner during the six-year civil war will be released at an unspecified later date. the government also plans a general review of the cases of about 1,800 members of somoza's now-disbanded national guard, ortega said
speaking to reporters saturday night, ortega said the former guardsmen all have been accused of human rights violations or crimes against humanity _ such as the indiscriminate shooting of civilians _ during the one-year revolution that brought the sandinistas to power
many of them have been sentenced to the maximum penalty of 30 years imprisonment, ortega said. the downfall of somoza, a rightist pro-american strongman, ended 42-years of iron-fisted rule by his family, usually enforced by the national guard
ortega said the case of each guardsmen will be sent to the organization of american states' interamerican human rights commission for review before a release is ordered to safeguard the sandinista government from criticism that it acted unfairly
on saturday, ortega said he had told gilberto schilittler, head of the u.n. delegation, that ``it is important to achieve the stabilization of the border zone with honduras and this is only possible with a multilateral force.''
ortega said that without a peacekeeping force, ``the united states can continue heating up the border ... provoking conflicts, increasing its presence to threaten nicaragua.''
the u.n. team inspected the border thursday and friday, scene of a reported incursion into honduras by sandinista army troops pursuing contra rebels
the sandinistas pardoned and released 900 political and rebel prisoners in october and november as a goodwill gesture in an unsuccessful effort to bring the contras to the bargaining table
but in a surprise move, leaders of the contra umbrella organization, the nicaraguan resistance, met with the sandinistas last week and agreed thursday on a 60-day cease-fire beginning april 1. further negotiations will follow to reach a more permanent truce
an informal cease-fire both sides had agreed to while the negotiations were in progress continued to hold sunday
an estimated 50,000 people have been killed or wounded since the contra war against the sandinistas began in november 1981
ortega said the two sides will meet again on monday in the little southern village of sapoa, near the costa rican border, to continue talks
the negotiations will now center on so-called ``truce areas'' where the contras can gather, and later turn in their weapons
sunday's amnesty was demanded by the contras as a condition for further talks. it is also called for under a regional peace plan that ortega and the four other central american presidents signed last august
the plan aims at negotiating an end to the contra war and to leftist guerrilla wars in el salvador and guatemala
in honduras, about 3,200 american troops, sent in two weeks ago by president reagan when sandinista troops allegedly entered honduras in pursuit of contra rebels, prepared to return home on monday
the reagan administration said they were sent both to bolster the honduran government and as a warning to the sandinistas against further incursions
court records scheduled to be unsealed this week may cast some light on death threats authorities say a prosecutor apparently fabricated
u.s. magistrate ronald j. hedges last week gave the government until wednesday to object to his decision to unseal about eight of 29 pages of transcripts of conversations he had with special assistant u.s. attorney judy g. russell about the threats
the discussions, from which defense attorneys were excluded, came during hearings feb. 1-5 on a request to extradite two sikhs accused by the indian government of terrorism in that nation
the hearings, which resulted in a decision to allow the pair to be extradited, took place amid extraordinary security because of alleged death threats to ms. russell and an anonymous letter to hedges. u.s. attorney samuel a. alito jr. disclosed last monday that the threats apparently were manufactured by ms. russell
no charges have been filed in connection with the alleged threats. alito said an internal affairs division of the justice department is investigating. he hasn't suggested any motive for the threats
alito has alleged that ms. russell cut out words from magazines to form threatening messages and mailed them to herself
in part of an affidavit hedges already released, ms. russell mentioned four mailed threats in requesting tight security at the extradition hearing
ms. russell also allegedly told fbi agents a threat was hand-delivered to her feb. 4 when she was staying in a secret hotel location under 24-hour guard. an fbi affidavit released last monday said none of the guards noticed anyone enter the area during the time she claimed to have received the threat
ronald kuby, attorney for sikh defendant sukhminder singh, also said ms. russell told the fbi a fabricated story about a suspect who allegedly shouted at her in a mall. a federal official, speaking on condition of anonymity, confirmed kuby's statement
her former colleagues in the u.s. attorney's office have refused to comment publicly, as has ms. russell's attorney robert fettweis. fettweis has said only that ms. russell is in seclusion in a ``private hospital.''
ms. russell left the u.s. attorney's office to enter private practice before the extradition hearing, and returned to handle it as a special assistant u.s. attorney
singh and the second sikh, ranjit singh gill, have asked a federal judge in new york to review hedges' extradition decision
alito has said he does not think the threats affected the extradition decision, but he wants a new hearing to avoid the appearance of impropriety. his office and defense attorneys are deciding how to proceed with the case. judge</head> 5th graf, ``pierce was xxx, to include his age; subs grafs 20-26 pvs (last seven grafs) with 11 grafs to add background on pierce, another comment from sheriff, and background on court race and county</note>
julian pierce was a rarity in racially troubled robeson county, respected by blacks, indians and whites, but many of his supporters believe he was slain because someone didn't want a lumbee indian to be a judge
there is absolute shock,'' the rev. mac legerton said sunday. ``there is a feeling among people that `oh my god, we tried to seek change through the electoral process, and look what happens ...
we are hoping that all the citizens will choose non-violent means to resolve our massive difficulties here.''
pierce's death early saturday from three shotgun blasts at point-blank range appeared to be the first time in the state that a candidate for political office had been murdered, said robert morgan, director of the state bureau of investigation. no one had been arrested sunday
pierce, 42, was running for a superior court judgeship and would have been the first lumbee indian to serve in the post in robeson county if he had been elected
pierce had been alone in his brick ranch house, which is flanked by farmland and another small house
someone was at the (kitchen) door and when he went to the door, they were waiting for him,'' robeson county sheriff hubert stone said
it just looked like he was actually assassinated,'' stone said saturday
the indians are going to have to take the law into their own hands ... to protect their selves, family and friends,'' a local resident, earl moore, said saturday at pierce's home
moore, who said he had known pierce for 15 years, said the candidate ``knew that something could happen'' to him. moore said he knew of a threat against pierce, but said he would talk only to federal officials in washington, not to county, state or federal officials in north carolina
there's a lot of leads that are being pursued,'' state investigator cuyler windham said sunday, declining to elaborate. ``we've interviewed numerous people, and we will continue to follow every lead that comes up.''
robeson county, which borders on south carolina, is 37 percent white, 37 percent indian and 26 percent black. it is one of the state's poorest counties, and has long been torn by racial animosity
activism, particularly by lumbees, has thrived since november 1986 when an unarmed lumbee was shot and killed by a sheriff's deputy
anger at what the indians call corrupt local government and entrenched racism boiled over most recently feb. 1, when two lumbees took hostages at the robesonian newspaper in lumberton, the county seat. eddie hatcher and timothy jacobs said they engineered the siege in order to attract attention
in a telephone interview from prison with the winston-salem journal saturday night, hatcher called on gov. jim martin to appoint a special prosecutor to investigate both his allegations and the pierce killing
how many dead indians and execution-style killings of our people shall it take before you, governor martin, bestow upon our people the long overdue justice we deserve?'' hatcher asked
about 100 people stood quietly outside pierce's home saturday
he didn't have any enemies,'' gladys freeman, a lumbee, said of pierce, a lawyer who resigned from his post as director of a legal-aid organization for the poor in january to run for the judgeship. ``who could hate him? no one could.''
it makes me think there's no hope for the indians,'' said janice locklear, also a lumbee. ``i'm so mad i could fight.''
people questioned outside pierce's home said they thought he would have won the election against joe freeman britt, a white who has been district attorney in the county for 14 years
they cited a vote earlier this month to consolidate the county's five school systems, which had been divided along racial lines. advocates of consolidation, largely lumbee and black, narrowly won the vote in this rural, underdeveloped county of 100,000 people
an impromptu news conference outside pierce's house by stone and morgan brought heckling from members of the crowd, who asked as many questions of the law enforcement authorities as did reporters
stone, a white, said he considered pierce a friend, and britt called the murder ``sad and tragic'' in a statement
pierce grew up in neighboring hoke county and worked in a virginia shipyard after graduating from college. he returned to north carolina and attended north carolina central university law school, then worked for the u.s. securities and exchange commission from 1976 to 1978
he then moved to robeson county to serve as the first director of lumbee river legal services, representing those too poor to afford lawyers and practicing public interest law
he was an easygoing guy. he never had no problem with anyone that i heard tell of. people liked him,'' stone said
the election effectively was to be decided may 3 _ the date of the democratic primary _ since no republicans were in the race. britt and pierce were the only candidates, and community leaders said they weren't sure if another candidate could be entered at this late date
robeson county had been given its own judicial district in order to give minorities a better chance of electing a judge. the county had previously been part of a larger district
at a rally in february, pierce said he was running for the post because minorities were not respected by the criminal justice system that they were not a part of
i promise you one thing _ if i'm elected judge, i'll be a just judge because i think we need that, but i won't see color,'' he said. say</head>
a state senator who told police he was shot by his wife after he returned home from a special legislative session improved from critical to serious condition sunday, a spokeswoman at lsu medical center said
greg tarver, 41, a second-term senator, told police that his wife, sabrina, shot him and that he didn't want to press charges, police chief charles gruber said at a news conference late saturday
she is not in custody. ... we are not looking for her,'' he said
mrs. tarver could not be located for comment sunday. nobody answered at the tarvers' home number. sam jones, who answered the telephone at the funeral home tarver runs, said the whole family was at the hospital. reporters there did not see mrs. tarver
tarver was in intensive care after 4{ hours of surgery, said hospital spokeswoman elaine king
doctors said they repaired blood vessels damaged by a .25-caliber bullet that tore through tarver's chest saturday
it's up to tarver whether to have his wife arrested, gruber said: ``if a victim doesn't wish to pursue a case, then you have no case. although we will try to put our case together in case he should change his mind.''
i feel sure that once we get everything together we will turn it all over to the district attorney and let him look at it and see what he thinks,'' said detective sgt. rick ware
charges often are not filed in domestic violence cases, said district attorney paul carmouche
the shooting happened less than an hour after tarver, one of a handful of blacks in the 39-member louisiana senate, returned from the special session in baton rouge. gruber said tarver's mother, balistine hopkins, reported the shooting
tarver, who will be 42 wednesday, was one of three blacks elected to the shreveport city council in 1978 _ the first blacks ever elected to the council
he became the city's first black state senator in 1984 after a bitter campaign against incumbent bill keith, who ran a television commercial showing police mug shots of tarver and listing 14 arrests from 1967 to 1973. most of the arrests were on charges of disturbing the peace and resisting arrest during civil rights protests
tarver was sworn in for a second four-year term march 14
