the april 8 vote also will prepare a new generation of leaders to take over after the aging ayatollah ruhollah khomeini dies
hardliners, such as interior minister ali akbar mohtashemi, who has close links to pro-iranian shiite moslem militants holding foreign hostages in lebanon, are expected to make some gains
abraham lincoln paid just $1,500 for the only house he ever owned, but nearly 150 years later $2.2 million has been spent to fix it up before it's reopened to the public this summer
back at that time, he got a good buy for his money,'' said gentry davis of the national park service. ``it was a corner lot and a prime location with easy access to downtown.''
a three-year renovation of lincoln's two-story frame house will enter its final phase wednesday when workers remove a vinyl polyester shroud that cloaked the structure and allowed restoration to continue through the winter
april fools day was the date of the first two save the pun dinners, but good friday falls on april 1 this year, causing ``mass'' confusion among punsters
instead, the dinner is sharing april 4 with the `oh! punning day' of the chicago white sox,'' joked joyce heitler, the dinner's organizer. ``we'll both have a ball.''
heitler is head of the chicago chapter of the international save the pun foundation
copper once was king in montana. but the monarch has been dethroned _ by gold
while few would conjure visions of a ``gold rush'' on par with those of the last century, there's no doubt that gold is fueling the state's fastest-growing industry
we are looking at a period of major upswing,'' said edward ruppell, head of the montana bureau of mines and geology. he expects a healthy amount of mining activity to continue as long as gold prices remain above $400 an ounce
jim jensen, executive director of the montana environmental information center, believes, ``we've got an old-fashioned gold rush on our hands.''
while the state may not be experiencing a flood of major mining companies, he said hordes of small one- or two-man placer mining operations are tucked away in the backcountry. ``they're up every gulch and coulee in the state,'' jensen said
the scope of the mining is hard to measure because, unlike the once-thriving copper industry centered in butte's huge open-pit mines and anaconda's giant smelter, the search for gold is scattered out of sight in the hills and mountains
people don't see in one spot the major impact mining has on the economy,'' said gary langley, executive director of the montana mining association
montana has four major precious metal mines operating now, employing about 900 people and producing more than 5 million ounces of gold and silver annually. seven more projects in some stage of planning could more than double both employment and yearly production
also, exploration is booming. the department of state lands, which reviews all major mining applications, estimates there are 450 exploration projects under way. the agency issued 111 exploration permits last year, twice the number recorded in 1982
with so much exploration and so many projects on the drawing board, ``i don't see that it's going to turn around,'' said kit walther, chief of the department's hardrock bureau
of the existing projects, the pegasus gold operation at zortman and landusky is the state's largest gold producer and the third largest supplier of silver. opened in 1979, it produces 100,000 ounces of gold and 200,000 ounces of silver per year
the state's largest underground mine near troy, operated by american smelting and refining co. since 1981, is the state's largest silver producer at 3.6 million ounces annually
the montana tunnels project south of helena, started in april 1986 and operated by pegasus, expects to mine 85,000 ounces of gold this year. the golden sunlight mine east of whitehall began in 1982 and produces up to 100,000 ounces of gold per year
the jardine joint venture, planned for three miles north of yellowstone national park, received state approval earlier this year and hopes for full production of 42,000 ounces of gold per year by mid-1989
u.s. borax and asarco inc. have proposed large silver mines in the cabinet mountains of northwestern montana that together would produce 11 million ounces of silver per year
langley said many of the mining ventures are centered on the same claims scoured by miners in montana's territorial days. new technology in the use of cyanide makes it easier to separate gold from rock and more elaborate machinery smoothes the task of moving 14 tons of earth to process one ounce of gold, he said
but the lure of gold is not without its problems
jensen said the department of state lands does not have the experienced staff necessary to monitor all the mining projects properly, especially those exempt from state review because their plans call for disturbing no more than five acres
who knows what these people are doing until some problem occurs,'' he said
jensen also complains that mining companies take too lightly the danger of cyanide leaking into rivers and streams, and that the state department is reluctant to require extensive environmental impact statements on projects. he also said the state needs reclamation standards to govern open-pit mines that dominate the precious metals industry
dennis hemmer, state lands commissioner, denies his agency shies away from environmental reviews. and langley said environmentalists' opposition to mining projects is based on admittedly poor mining practices of the past. the industry is more conscious of the environmental effects of its work than before, he said
but jensen is suspicious, noting the state has yet to reject a single mine application
maybe there should be a day when the state said, `here is a proposal to mine where the risk to other values clearly outweighs the benefits,''' he said. ``is mining something that can always go on and always has the highest value no matter what? i don't think so.''
if you don't agree with one oil-price forecast for the 1990s, just flip the page
projections of per-barrel future prices are ranging from as low as $12 to as high as $46. with oil markets currently volatile and uncertain, the future appears anything but clear
some forecasters see a continuing market glut, others see tightening oil supplies. the organization of petroleum exporting countries is viewed both as on its way back to defining oil prices and as a fading force
perhaps never before has the crystal ball of oil price forecasting been so buried in a blizzard of logic, numbers and ultimately, guesses
since late 1985, prices for west texas intermediate crude _ the benchmark gauge of u.s. prices _ have fluctuated from below $10 to above $20. in recent months, the figure has gyrated between $15 and $20 per 42-gallon barrel
although opec members agreed in december to keep the cartel's official price at $18 per barrel, reports of overproduction and price discounting by opec members have kept the market soft
that picture could change dramatically in a few short years, according to some experts. chuck strain, director of energy research at lovett, mitchell, webb &amp; garrison inc. in houston, projects that oil prices will rise from current levels to about $27 in 1991, hitting a level that will last, with fluctuations, throughout much of the decade
we're basically more optimistic about crude than most other people,'' strain said. ``the kuwaitis and saudis will regain control of pricing in 1989-1990.''
saudi arabia and kuwait are two of the cartel's leading producers
he believes increasing demand for opec oil will enable the cartel to enforce a firmer pricing line due to strong gasoline appetite and the limited attractiveness of energy alternatives
the reason we level it off at $27 is that the saudis will raise the level of price to where it is below what would encourage alternate (non-opec) forms of energy,'' said strain, who also forecasts neither strong growth nor deep economic retrenchment during the next several years
richard s. pzena, senior research analyst for sanford c. bernstein &amp; co., inc. in new york, believes oil prices will reach $30 in 1992, rising to $36-$37 in 1995, gauged in 1988 dollars
in my mind the issue is that the world needs opec oil and opec ought to try to charge the highest price it can get away with if it is being rational, which is the highest it can charge without losing market share,'' said pzena
prices can probably keep going up to about $30 before you see a whole new category of (non-opec) oil become economic,'' pzena said
richard gordon, director of market research for petroleum finance co. in washington, says he anticipates oil prices rising to $29 to $46 per barrel in 1988 dollars in the first half of the 1990s
we believe it (the price rise) is going to come in first half of 1990s, most probably in 1992,'' said gordon, who says his research has been based on examination of oil prices over more than a century
he estimates oil prices are subject to economic cycles of roughly 20 years from peak to peak and trough to trough
we believe there are fundamental market factors that create this cycle and make it keep recurring, and those factors are not related to opec, (and) they are not a function of market shock,'' gordon said. ``they are related to long-term shifts in market fundamentals in the oil and gas sectors.''
he believes the oil industry currently is focusing on trying to gain returns on safe projects, rather than exploring new oil sources
the industry has in effect begun a long-term strategic depletion of its reserves,'' gordon said
but joseph stanislaw, managing director of cambridge energy research associates, believes oil prices are unlikely to rise past $24 per barrel over the next seven years. he even has gone so far as to say prices could drop as low of $12 per barrel at some point in the 1990s
stanislaw said in a recent speech that the oil industry should pay more attention to the individual motives of pivotal oil-exporting countries such as saudi arabia, iran and iraq, and less attention to opec as a cartel
forget opec _ i can't emphasize that enough,'' stanislaw said, adding that growth in non-opec production has diluted opec's influence. ``every time we look, we find oil.''
another price bear is dale steffes, founder of houston-based planning &amp; forecasting consultants, who believes oil prices in 1995 are unlikely to be any higher than $14, measured in 1988 dollars
why somebody thinks we are going to have high prices is beyond me,'' he said. ``there is too much oil in the world, it's overpriced and there is not enough demand.''
a prominent arab oil expert, describing the present oil market as ``very weak,'' warned sunday that the failure of opec members to abide by their output quotas could lead to a collapse of oil prices
abdel-aziz al-watari, acting secretary-general of the organization of arab oil exporting countries, said a recent arab energy conference held in baghdad, iraq, concluded that ``the oil market is very weak at present because of the absolute slowdown in oil demand and because projections of increase in demand have failed to come through.''
in an interview with the kuwait news agency, watari said this situation could last for five years. he called for ``a profound commitment and high degree of credibility on the part of opec states to retain the present reference price of $18 a barrel.''
the situation, he said, also required ``a high degree of cooperation'' from producers outside the 13-nation organization of petroleum exporting countries. seven of oapec's members, including influential saudi arabia, also are members of opec
on friday, crude oil prices firmed slightly in response to reports that members of opec's pricing committee would meet next month to discuss ways to stabilize the market
on the new york mercantile exchange, the may contract for west texas intemediate, the benchmark u.s. crude, settled at $17.03 per barrel, up 7 cents from thursday's close
saudi oil minister hisham nazer on wednesday called for an emergency meeting of the pricing committee amid reports some of the cartel's members have been violating production quotas and prices decreed by opec
the failure of states in opec to stick to the production sharing will set the stage for a price decline, and any extraordinary increase in production could lead to the collapse of the price system in the foreseeable future,'' watari warned
in riyadh, nazer discussed cooperation between opec and non-opec members with malaysian foreign minister datu al-haj abu al-hasan ibn al-haj omar, whose country is not a member of the cartel
the official saudi press agency quoted nazer as saying that during the meeting, the two ministers ``reviewed the role of non-opec producers in helping stabilize the oil market.'' out</head>
corporate merger specialists, tired of subsidizing co-worker salaries, quit and create their own company. one of the country's biggest law firms splinters in a feud over money and expansion. an advertising giant teeters when executives join a newly formed rival, wooing valued clients
from madison avenue to wall street, disgruntled managers are jumping ship with increasing frequency, a trend that reflects their frustration at working for someone else and fear of getting victimized in an uncertain climate of corporate takeovers, experts say
companies are going to have to do more to give individuals the ability to function as entrepreneurs,'' said frank palma, senior vice president of executive search at goodrich &amp; sherwood co., a management consulting firm. ``if they don't, we'll see more people venture into their own businesses.''
to some extent, management analysts say, many talented executives feel they have a better survival chance if they start their own companies, rather than remain loyal to employers that could suddenly become takeover targets
instead of being the swallowee, why not do the swallowing?,'' palma said. ``i just see a change in the perspective of good many people, because of all the insecure aspects of being a member of the corporate environment. going into your own business is not perceived as such a big risk as it was 20 years ago.''
denise rousseau, associate professor of organizational behavior at northwestern university's kellogg graduate management school, said the urge to jump ship also is a result of a growing service economy, in which the products are largely thoughts and ideas
we just simply have a greater portion of the population in knowledge- based businesses,'' she said. ``people can more readily take with them the wherewithal of their work.''
some of the most visible departures came after the october stock market collapse, which shrank wall street profits and forced austerity upon securities firms that had grown fat and complacent. many takeover specialists grew annoyed over directives to take salary cuts, especially when their dealmaking remained one of the few post-crash moneymakers
at first boston corp., co-heads of the investment banking unit quit and formed their own firm. the co-head of shearson lehman hutton's mergers department quit after a reported clash with the chief executive
last week, salomon brothers inc. lost one of its celebrities, former white house budget director david stockman, who joined the much smaller blackstone group as head of corporate acquisitions. in addition, merrill lynch &amp; co. and kidder peabody &amp; co. have suffered defections by some of their brightest stars
the splintering also has affected the legal profession, an area in which up until recently mergers and the growth of super-sized firms had been common. one of the biggest examples came last year with the demise of the nation's fourth-biggest law firm: finley, kumble, wagner, heine, underberg, manley, myerson &amp; casey, which once had 700 attorneys in offices nationwide
greed, excessive expansion, salaries paid with borrowed money and a management struggle at the top caused lawyers to start resigning en masse starting last summer, according to press accounts of finley kumble's collapse
another publicized episode of ship-jumping came more recently when the chairman, president and more than a dozen other key people at advertising giant lord, geller, federico, einstein inc. quit to form a new agency
the mass departures stemmed from an autonomy dispute with lord geller's british parent wpp group plc. fearing the exodus would collapse the firm and send clients over to the new rival, wpp went to court to sue the defectors
this type of litigation, which centers around an area called intellectual property rights, likely will increase as the number of employees who quit to form their own companies rises, experts say
there's a fine line between what is owned by a company and what is owned by the individual who works for it,'' said edith weiner, a partner at the management consulting firm of weiner, edrich, brown inc
in the service business, we're finding more problems with intellectual property. it's expanding beyond the issue of taking clients, into technical knowledge and ideas,'' she said
the technological revolution itself has erased some of the physical impediments of quitting and starting your own company, she said, particularly because of the vast sources of information available via computer
it's very easy to walk out the door. all you have to do is walk out with it on a (computer) disk,'' she said. ``you used to have to take file cabinets.''
steve florio talked to his longtime advertising agency nearly every day, but says he was as surprised as anyone when lord, geller, federico, einstein inc. began to unravel 10 days ago
it was a friday afternoon and florio, the president and chief executive of new yorker magazine inc., called to discuss some minor changes in an ad layout
he asked for arthur einstein jr., a founding partner at the highly regarded agency that has been making new yorker ads for 17 years
einstein wasn't there. ``his secretary told me arthur and dick lord had resigned _ that six of them had walked out,'' florio said
the walkout on march 18 was followed by other defections, and within a week florio had decided he would drop lord geller as his ad agency. other clients, including giant international business machines corp., said they are reassessing the situation, too
the events have been the talk of madison avenue, where business and personal relations often seem inextricably bound
einstein said he and his five colleagues left to start a new agency because they felt they couldn't operate as they wanted to under the management of wpp group plc, which acquired lord geller last summer
since the six top executives left, an estimated 30 of lord geller's 325 employees have quit, some joining their old colleagues at a new agency called lord, einstein, o'neill &amp; partners
lord geller has gone to court, charging that the departed executives breached fiduciary duties and conspired to take business from the agency. the firm asks that the defectors be enjoined from soliciting lord geller clients and employees. a state supreme court hearing has been set for monday
wpp, which is headed by the financially-adept martin sorrell, bought lord geller as part of its $566 million purchase in july 1987 of jwt group inc., which also owned the advertising giant j. walter thompson co
lord geller and j. walter thompson had been operated independently since lord geller was acquired by thompson in 1974
einstein said he and his partners grew increasingly disaffected under wpp's ownership, but sorrell refused to discuss selling the agency to them
they objected to wpp's reported plans to set up a network of agencies in europe that could boast an affiliation with lord geller
they bristled when sorrell prohibited lord geller from competing for general motors corp.'s new saturn automobile account, reportedly for fear of offending ford motor co., j. walter thompson's biggest client
the new yorker's florio said einstein had never mentioned that he and his colleagues were having problems under wpp management. after being told einstein had left the agency, florio said, he phoned einstein and told him that he wanted to continue working with him
sorrell stopped by on monday to talk with florio and asked him to defer a decision on moving the account because two respected admakers, dick thomas and chuck griffith, would be staying on it
but when florio called griffith the next day to discuss the changes he had in mind for the ad, he was told griffith ``had left for good.''
he asked for thomas, was switched over and then told thomas had ``left the agency an hour ago.''
florio asked to talk with sorrell, who told him there were plenty of talented people at the agency to get the ad done. but florio didn't like the idea that you could ``just slap somebody on the account,'' and told sorrell to ``freeze my campaign for the time being.''
florio said he was now genuinely worried about the ad deadline, and called the lord geller executive who normally placed the new yorker ads. he was told she had left the agency as well
all the creative people and the media people that i had dealt with had resigned. i literally don't know anybody there,'' florio said
on friday, florio said he planned to send a letter next week dismissing the agency and would take the account to lord einstein
the new yorker is a relatively small account, spending about $1.5 million on advertising this year. lord geller handles billings of about $245 million a year, which in turn is dwarfed by the $3.2 billion that thompson bills
the walkout touched off a scramble by other agencies for lord geller's accounts. florio said he heard from six other agencies in the past week
jerry della femina, who heads della femina travisano &amp; partners, is among them. he bets most clients won't move to the new agency given the legal challenges that lord geller has raised
della femina said some lord geller clients may say ``a plague on both their houses'' and look for a new agency
bowing out of the fight to take over american standard inc. hasn't left black &amp; decker chairman nolan d. archibald on the ropes
he's still on the lookout for another good acquisition and won't rule out another hostile takeover bid. and in the eyes of wall street, walking away from the bidding war may have raised his standing a notch or two
we have a list of companies we've been looking at for more than a year,'' he said in an interview. ``american standard was at the top of that list; when another company hits the top we'll go after it. it could be a week or six months.''
archibald wants to make black &amp; decker a home-related-products powerhouse. the plan is to take advantage of the towson toolmaker's worldwide distribution network and marketing skills by adding new products, a process that began with its acquisition of general electric's home appliance group
we don't want to be a conglomerate, but we do want to become a much bigger company than we are now,'' he said
he won't say how big, but taking over american standard would have created one of the baltimore-washington area's largest companies, with sales approaching $5 billion
he has enlisted the corps d'elite of investment banking shearson lehman hutton, goldman sachs, morgan stanley and first boston, among others to beat the bushes for a suitable match
had the run at american standard been successful, archibald envisioned weaving its strong plumbing and fixtures lines into black &amp; decker's consumer-oriented building product lines. the merger would have made black &amp; decker a key player in the new housing market and complemented its strong position in professional power tools
archibald said black &amp; decker has its eye on several companies and added that its next acquisition target could be smaller than american standard. it could also be a friendly one
there are a lot of companies out there up for sale due to past mergers and spinoffs. a lot of the opportunities we're looking at fall into that category,'' he said
however, a few public companies are also being considered, and archibald doesn't rule out the possibility of making another hostile bid
archibald said he's not chagrined at losing american standard to kelso &amp; co., which beat out black &amp; decker with a $2.5 billion offer the towson-based power tool maker wasn't willing to match. he said there is nothing he would have done differently from a tactical standpoint
we could have bought the company, but the bidding got to a level that wasn't in line with our financial objectives,'' he said
though the towson manufacturer lost the contest for american standard, archibald walked away from the possibility of overpaying and diluting near-term profits and pocketed a $25 million payoff from kelso _ which looks good to wall street
they played a good, well-orchestrated game, but in the end decided it wasn't worth risking diluting earnings. knowing when to walk away and getting paid for it demonstrates the maturity of this company's management team,'' said bentley offutt, president of offutt securities inc. in towson
people were relieved,'' said robert o' grady, a securities salesman for alex. brown &amp; sons in new york. ``they were loading up with debt to purchase a $36 stock. now the company has returned to what it was two months ago, a beautifully run company with great earnings potential.''
